## Pages 241–260

### Chapter 6 Conclusion: From Prehistory to the Modern Era in Seventy Years

- Gordon's chapter 6 assessment: information/entertainment advances before 1940 could be argued to have made more cultural difference than those after 1940
- 1870: total isolation; 1940: 40 million people listened to Seabiscuit race together; Dorothy's "Toto" moment brought millions into color
- Print media: readership of books, magazines, newspapers exploded post-1870 (near-universal literacy; public libraries)
- Communication speed: before 1844 telegraph, limited to railroad/horse/sailing ship speed; never so radical an increase in communication speed as the 1844 telegraph
- Gone with the Wind 1939 Santa Barbara pre-screening: theater management locked doors, posted guards; audience rose to feet at the main title; "Selznick was moved to tears"; audience felt "sense of privilege" they had witnessed something they could tell their grandchildren about
- Gordon's central contrast: Was 1940 more distant from 1870 than 2015 is from 1940? He will revisit in chapter 12

---

### Chapter 7: Nasty, Brutish, and Short — Illness and Early Death

**Chapter Overview**
- Opening epigraph from George Rosen (1958): virtual eradication of communicable diseases spread by water, milk, food, insects, rodents — typhoid, yellow fever, diphtheria, malaria now "a thing of the past"
- This chapter: improvements in life expectancy — the dimension of the standard of living not captured by market purchases
- The value of reduced mortality (especially infant mortality) before 1940 was approximately equal to the value of ALL growth in market-purchased goods/services over the same period
- Central surprise: annual rate of improvement in life expectancy was TWICE as fast in the first half of the 20th century as in the last half — counterintuitive given antibiotics, cancer treatment, CT/MRI
- Cutler and Miller: "together with the late 19th century, no other documented period in American history [as 1900–1940] witnessed such rapidly falling mortality rates"

**The Dimensions of Improvement, 1870–1940**
- No improvement in mortality rates or life expectancy before 1870; most series show no improvement before 1890
- 1870–79: male life expectancy at age 20 IDENTICAL to that in 1750–79; female at 20 actually LOWER
- Infant mortality rate: 215 per 1,000 births in 1880 — unchanged from Tudor England (200-250)
- No improvement 1850–1880; steep decline 1890–1950; much slower after 1950
- Out of every 1,000 births: 188 lives saved by improvements 1880–1950 vs. only 21 additional lives saved 1950–2010
- Life expectancy at birth improved at 0.32 years/year during 1890–1950 vs. 0.15 years/year during 1950–98 — twice as fast in early period
- For life expectancy at age 70: reversed — 0.03 years/year (1890–1950) vs. 0.05 years/year (1950–98) — after people survived childhood, their conditional life expectancy did not improve radically
- Bizarre coincidence: John Adams (age 90) and Thomas Jefferson (age 83) both died July 4, 1826 — 50th anniversary of Declaration of Independence; Americans who survived childhood always had potential to live long
- Human heights: declined steadily for those born 1830–1890, then rose most rapidly 1890–1930 (consistent with health deterioration before 1890)
- Massachusetts: life expectancy improved more during 1890–1920 than in the entire century before 1890

**Urban vs. Rural Mortality**
- Urban areas: consistently higher mortality due to contaminated food, contagious disease spread, standing water, airless tenements
- 1900 white life expectancy at birth: rural males 46.0 years; urban males only 39.1 years (rural/urban differential ~half that for females)
- "Urbanization moved people from lower to higher mortality regimes, exacting a price for the increased economic opportunity of the city"
- Late 19th-century industrialization WORSENED pollution: "Earth was scarred by mining pits and railway tracks; air was fouled and darkened by factory soot; water was polluted by industrial wastes"
- Survival rate comparison: of 100 born, surviving to age 5 was 75% in 1870 vs. 94% in 1940 vs. 99% in 1997
- Half of 1870 cohort dead by age 50; 1940 cohort 50% survival until age 67; 1997 cohort not until age 77
- Kevin Murphy and Robert Topel: "In 1900, nearly 18 percent of males born in the United States died before their first birthday; today, cumulative mortality does not reach 18 percent until age 62"
- Racial gap: 1900 life expectancy for nonwhite males = 33 years; white males = 48 years (15-year gap). By 1940: narrowed to 11 years (52 vs. 63). Jim Crow policy explicitly denied nonwhite areas running water and sanitary sewage — direct cause of shorter life expectancy

**The Critical Finding: Medicine Had Little to Do with It**
- Infectious diseases accounted for 37% of deaths in 1900; by 1955, less than 5%; by 2009, only 2%
- Chronic conditions (heart disease, strokes, cancer): increased from 7% to 60% of deaths over the same period
- 1918–19 Spanish flu pandemic: 675,000 Americans died (small fraction of global 20-50 million deaths, exceeding WWI fatalities); influenza A virus not isolated until 1933; first vaccine not until 1944; "Spanish" label arose because wartime censors suppressed news except from neutral Spain
- McKinlay and McKinlay finding: most decline in tuberculosis and influenza mortality had already occurred BEFORE medical interventions were introduced — "3.5 percent probably represents a reasonable upper-limit estimate of the total contribution of medical measures to the decline in mortality in the United States since 1900"
- Higgs: "changes in medical practice during the period 1870–1920 could, at best, have contributed only negligibly to the decline in the rural crude death rate"
- All of the decline in infectious disease mortality achieved by 1955 — BEFORE medical care spending began its rise from 4% of GDP (mid-1950s) to 17% (2010)

**Water and Sewers: The Central Explanation**
- "From time immemorial the human race had recognized that, if health was to be maintained, such bodily wastes as urine and feces must be kept rigidly separated from food and drink"
- Clean water filtration/chlorination likely "the most important public health intervention of the twentieth century"
- Urban households with filtered water: 0.3% (1880) → 1.5% (1890) → 6.3% (1900) → 25% (1910) → 42% (1925) → 93% (1940)
- By 1940: 83% of urban households had sole use of indoor toilet
- Cutler and Miller: chlorination advanced 1906–1918; filtration 1906–1922; death rate from typhoid fever fell by factor of 5 between 1900 and 1920
- Their estimate: clean water filtration and chlorination explain 50% of overall mortality reduction 1900–1936, 75% of decline in infant mortality, 67% of decline in child mortality
- Rural America bypassed: continued using shallow wells, springs, cisterns; milk not pasteurized; privies for waste — "the public health movement that triumphed in the larger American cities between 1890 and 1920 almost completely by-passed the countryside"
- Memphis yellow fever epidemic 1878: killed 10% of city's population; cause unknown; "victims literally turned yellow and died in agony" — major impetus for water infrastructure investment
- Early municipal water systems imperfect: animal waste on streets pushed into drains and ultimately into drinking water; sewers emptied into rivers/lakes used as water sources
- Additional motivation for urban water: fire fighting, street sprinkling, sewer flushing — towns competed for water supply because it enhanced property values
- 80% of decline in total mortality rate accounted for by four categories: diarrheal diseases, typhoid, tuberculosis, diphtheria

**The Pasteur Revolution and Behavioral Change**
- "Pasteur Revolution" 1880–1900: "pathogenic organisms were discovered at the average rate of one a year"
- NYC public health laboratory (est. 1892): within two years developed first diphtheria antitoxin; vaccination program reduced death rate from 785 per 100,000 (1894) to 1.1 per 100,000 (1950) — a major cause of death completely wiped out within 60 years
- Research extended to tuberculosis, dysentery, pneumonia, typhoid, scarlet fever, and the role of milk in disease
- Behavioral change: Pasteur theory changed parents' (especially mothers') behavior → Mokyr and Stein household production function for health
- Running water improved personal cleanliness: baths had been at best Saturday-night luxury when water had to be hand-carried
- Air pollution was severe: Chicago — "smoke has a peculiar aggressive individuality"; Kipling: "Its air is dirt"; Kansas City hog stench made Oscar Wilde say "they made granite eyes weep"; NYC air described as worse than "any dumping ground, no sewer, no vault"

---

## Pages 261–280

### Chapter 7 (continued): Health, Medicine, Hospitals, and Insurance

**Food Adulteration as an Industrial-Age Problem**
- Food adulteration was NOT an ancient problem — it was a NEW problem created by industrialization and urbanization
- Pre-1870: most food grown at home or bought from neighbors; households could protect themselves
- Post-1870 urbanization: food produced in factories, shipped long distances, no mechanical refrigeration; new chemical processes allowed adulteration disguised with coloring agents
- Milk: "a water shortage would put the milkman out of business … all [dealers] required was a water pump to boost two quarts of milk to a gallon … to improve the color of milk from diseased cattle they frequently added molasses, chalk, or plaster of Paris"
- As late as 1900: "the nation's milk supply was seriously contaminated with tuberculosis, typhoid, scarlet fever, diphtheria, and streptococcal germs"
- Even beer adulterated: "A man stands about as good a chance of being struck by lightning as of buying pure brandy in New York"
- NYC meat supply in early 1880s: reached stockyards through residential streets "strewing manure and trailing clouds of flies"; remainder from "diseased cows fed on distillery swill in the city's notoriously filthy dairies"; children played in ditches draining slaughterhouses

**The Pure Food and Drug Act (1906)**
- New York's Ladies' Protective Health Association (LPHA, est. 1884): first political movement led by women; forced slaughterhouse reforms; fiercely resisted by industry lobbying
- February 1906: Upton Sinclair's *The Jungle* published — intended as "the Uncle Tom's Cabin of the labor movement"; described meat "without being washed, pushed from room to room in rotten box carts, all the while collecting dirt, splinters, floor filth, and the expectoration of tubercular and other diseased workers"
- Instant bestseller; caught President Theodore Roosevelt's attention because it accused federal meat inspectors of taking bribes; top federal officials confirmed conditions nearly as bad as Sinclair depicted
- After government report and shocked newspaper coverage in early June 1906: "trade in lard, sausage, and canned goods came almost to a standstill…. Restaurants reported a vast decline in business"
- June 30, 1906: Congress passed, and Roosevelt signed, the Pure Food and Drug Act — established ancestor of today's FDA; newspapers hailed it as "the most important piece of legislation ever passed by Congress"
- Sinclair's *Jungle* "confirmed and publicized what people already knew or suspected" — was "merely the final, spectacular, fictionalized climax" to "long agitation" by women's organizations, food chemists, journalists, and reformers

**Pharmacies and Drug Regulation**
- Pre-1870: virtually unregulated; "drug adulteration was reputedly so common that doctors customarily prescribed excessive dosages on the assumption that the medication's strength had been substantially reduced"
- Three classes of drugs: (1) legitimate therapeutics — aspirin, morphine, quinine, diphtheria antitoxin; (2) patent medicines — heavily advertised miracle cures, mostly colored water and alcohol; (3) narcotics — opium, cocaine, heroin, widely available
- Chinese immigrants (recruited for transcontinental railway) established opium dens in San Francisco by the 1880s; cocaine and opiates were common treatments for pain, coughs, sleep — no prescriptions required
- Symbiotic relationship: newspapers suppressed coverage of drug dangers in exchange for drug company advertising revenue
- WCTU (1898 pamphlet): U.S. "seemed to be radically becoming a nation of cocaine fiends"
- 1906 Pure Food and Drug Act: first step — required labeling of alcohol, morphine, cocaine, heroin, cannabis, but did not prohibit them; 1914–1930s: further legislation banned these drugs including Prohibition (1920–1933)
- 1938 FDA legislation (successor to 1906 act): required FDA pre-approval of new drugs AND doctors' prescriptions for many drugs — completely changed drug marketing from advertising to consumers toward advertising to doctors; still serves as foundation of FDA regulation today
- Rate of discovery of effective drugs increased rapidly after 1935 sulfonamide drugs and penicillin during WWII

**What Did Doctors Do? (Pre-1940)**
- 1929: total health care expenditures = 2.3% of GDP vs. 16.6% in 2013
- 1870: 75% of population rural; many towns too small to support a single doctor; doctor fee included base charge PLUS per-mile charge; one doctor: "half of his life in the mud and the other half in the dust"
- Rural areas relied on midwives and unpaid female neighbors to tend sick; "most pioneers' first response to sickness was to employ folk remedies and tender loving care"
- Local general store sold opium tincture; whiskey used for pain ("for indigestion, a solution of rhubarb bitters or cayenne pepper mixed with whiskey was rubbed into the abdomen, often combined with whiskey and water taken internally")
- Motor vehicles transformed doctor mobility: "Besides making house calls in one-half the time, there is something about the auto that is infatuating, and the more you ride the more you want to ride"
- 1870: virtually no specialist surgeons; surgeon said in 1876 "it was safe to affirm that there is not a medical man on this continent who devotes himself exclusively to the practice of surgery"
- Two major surgical obstacles: (1) no reliable anesthetics, (2) postoperative sepsis killed half of major surgery patients — "a common report by surgeons was: operation successful but the patient died"
- Doctors/physicians ratio: peaked at 17.6 per 10,000 in the 1850s; fell to 12.5 in 1929 (due to Flexner report closures); then rose to 25.6 in 1990, 31.6 in 2009
- Hospital beds per 10,000: doubled from 47 in 1910 to 93 in 1940; then declined in postwar years as hospital stays shortened

**The Hospital: From Cesspool to Modern Medicine**
- 1870: hospitals more like nursing homes; only 120 hospitals in 1873; grew to 6,000 by 1920
- 1870–1880s: hospital = dumping ground for lower classes; "repositories of filth and infection"; Bellevue Hospital 1872 visitor: "The loathsome smell sickened me. The condition of the beds and patients was unspeakable. The one nurse slept in the bathroom and the tub was filled with filthy rubbish"
- Postoperative sepsis killed ~50% of major surgery patients
- Key advances: Joseph Lister (Glasgow Royal Infirmary, just after Civil War) → antiseptics using carbolic acid; 1879 Listerine named after him
- Symbol of pre-antiseptic era: President Garfield (1881) — assassin's bullet survived; doctors probed with fingers and unsterilized instruments; Garfield died from secondary infection
- Hospitals in mid/upper classes avoided — sick endured at home; even accident victims taken home rather than to hospitals
- Boston Evening Transcript columnist (1888): hospital gives "only sickness to think about morning, noon, and night"
- Hospital support: voluntary philanthropy of wealthy + religious orders + ethnic associations; doctors worked gratis for experience
- Free patients stayed average 5 weeks in late 1870s; hospitals struggled to limit free patient stays
- Childbirth: only 5% of women delivered in hospitals in 1900; by 1921, more than half in major cities; by 1939, 50% of all women / 75% of urban women; by 1960, 95% of all women — "The fashion changed" (Rose Kennedy)
- Nursing schools: grew from 3 in 1873 to 432 by 1900 to 1,129 by 1910; previously nursing considered at same social level as cleaning women
- By 1926: 6,800 hospitals; 44% had clinical laboratories; 41% had X-ray departments; 28% government-owned, 72% church/private/nonprofit
- By 1920s: beds divided into "first-class and steerage" — private/semiprivate for paying patients, charity wards for indigent; racial segregation of wards was standard

**Medical Schools and the Flexner Report**
- 1870: only 60 medical schools; most had 2-year programs of 18 weeks each; no admissions requirements; no grades; virtually no anatomy, physiology, or clinical training
- For-profit "diploma mills" — "a degree" in medicine available for $5–$10 depending on quality of paper diploma printed on
- Johns Hopkins Hospital (1889) and Medical School (1893) set the high standard
- Doctors hostile to germ theory: "well-known physicians would get up and leave the hall when medical papers were being read which emphasized the germ theory of disease"
- 1910: Abraham Flexner published devastating report (commissioned by Carnegie Foundation, at AMA's indirect request); visited all medical schools — institutions expecting financial gifts received guillotine instead
- Flexner: "touted laboratories consisted of a few vagrant test tubes squirreled away in a cigar box; corpses reeked because of the failure to use disinfectant in the dissecting rooms. Libraries had no books"
- Result: most for-profit medical schools shut down; reduced doctors per person; raised quality but also reduced supply → higher fees

**Medical Costs and the Failure of Universal Health Insurance**
- Pre-1910: medical costs not an important issue; house calls cheap; extra charge per mile traveled
- 1925: two-thirds of disabled patients treated at home by doctors, one-third in hospitals
- Patients had to pay multiple providers: "In some instances there may be eight or ten separate charges — one each from the family physician and several specialists, one or more for laboratory tests, another from the hospital for room and board..."
- Seven ways patients responded to high costs (mid-1920s): free dispensaries; free care from family physician; paying bill "as a matter of pride"; fraternal/union sickness funds; avoidance of treatment; patronizing quack doctors; self-treatment with patent medicines
- Commercial insurance already practiced cream-skimming, age limitations, pre-existing conditions exclusions
- Theodore Roosevelt's 1912 Progressive Party platform: "protection of home life against the hazards of sickness, irregular employment, and old age through the adoption of a system of social insurance adapted to American use" — model was Germany (1883), UK (1911)
- 1917: proponent lamented "Germany's heroic method of attacking it as a national evil through government machinery seems to us to belong almost to another planet"
- Chicago 1917 survey: 1 in 4 workers lost at least 1 week's wages due to sickness over prior year; for that subgroup, 13.6% of annual income lost
- 1930 national commission: top 3.5% of families with largest medical bills paid 1/3 of all national medical care costs — middle class hospital stays could equal 1/3 to 1/2 of annual income
- FDR New Deal achieved unemployment compensation and Social Security but omitted universal health insurance — reason: AMA opposition so fierce that FDR feared old-age pensions would also fail if medical care was included
- "The Great Depression improved the health of the average insured worker" — absurd claim that arose because employers fired unhealthy workers first, leaving healthier workers in the insured funds

---

## Pages 281–300

### Chapter 7 (continued): Accidents, Homicides, and Valuing Life Expectancy

**Death from Accidents**
- Electric light safety benefit often overlooked: 5,000–6,000 Americans/year previously died from lamp accidents (adulterated oil, spills, breakages, failing to lower wicks before blowing out)
- President Harrison (1892): "American workmen are subjected to peril of life and limb as great as a soldier in time of war"
- Railroad deaths in 1898–1900 were roughly equal to British Army losses in the three-year Boer War
- Peak railroad fatalities: 11,800 in 1907 = 138 per million population; declined to 35 in 1940; below 10 after 1970
- U.S. railroad fatality rate 1911–15 was 6x higher than contemporary Germany, Austria, and UK — due to lower construction standards (grade crossings not separated, wooden bridges, no platform fences)
- 1904: General Slocum paddle steamer on East River — bolted-down lifeboats, rotting life jackets; 1,000 of 1,300 passengers died
- 1915: Eastland capsized on Chicago River — 844 Western Electric employees killed at a company party
- Motor vehicle fatalities first exceeded railroad deaths in 1918; doubled railroad deaths by 1921
- Motor vehicle fatality rate per 100 million miles: 45 in 1909 → 22 in 1922 → 11 in 1939 → 1.3 in 2008 (40x improvement)
- Early cars: "weak brakes, tires that blew out, headlights that glared, plate-glass windows that made them easy to flip … no seat belts and often soft roofs or no roofs at all … no drivers' education requirements, no driving exams, no vision tests, no age limits, and in most places no speed limits"

**Homicides**
- Deaths from homicides historically ran at roughly half the rate of auto fatalities
- U.S. homicide rate 7–10x higher than any European country in the early twentieth century
- Pattern is a U-shape: high 1900–1933, low 1933–1960s, high again into 1980s
- Two peaks: 1933 (end of Prohibition) and 1980 (peak of drug violence)
- New England had homicide rates similar to England in 1900; highest rates in southern tier (Louisiana led)
- Western frontier towns: death rates per 100,000 could reach 100 (vs. 1 in 1900 England)
- Steven Pinker's explanation: democracy "came too early" to America — in Europe, the state had long disarmed people and acquired monopoly on violence; American south relied on "self-help justice"
- Scotch-Irish origins of southern highlanders (from mountainous British frontier) → cultural norm of settling disputes violently
- 2007: African Americans homicide victims at nearly 10x the rate of whites
- Black-on-black homicides in NYC rose from 3x to 13x white-on-white rate between 1850 and 1950; Great Migration carried this pattern to Chicago and Detroit

**Valuing Life Expectancy (Nordhaus Framework)**
- Central theme: great inventions' welfare benefits far exceed their measured GDP contribution
- Motor vehicles example: GDP accounts miss health and aesthetic benefits from retiring horses (manure, urine, carcasses)
- Nordhaus calculations: value of improvements in life expectancy during 1900–1950 was AS LARGE AS the growth rate of real GDP per capita from all other reasons combined
- With health capital included: 1900–1950 annual GDP growth per capita = 4.2% (vs. conventional 2.05%); 1950–2000 = 3.5% (vs. conventional 2.1%)
- Key conclusion: health-augmented growth rate in first half of 20th century was substantially HIGHER than in second half (despite official GDP measures suggesting the opposite)
- The decline in mortality contributed more to welfare before 1940 than after because infant mortality improvements save more life-years than extending life at age 65

**Chapter 7 Conclusion**
- Rate of improvement in life expectancy at birth 1890–1950: DOUBLE the rate in 1950–98
- 1927 summary of medical gap: "That knowledge is at hand to prevent much of the suffering and premature death caused by disease is avowed by well-known leaders in the field of medicine. The health field has a woefully ineffective distribution service… We know how to do a lot of things which we don't do, or do on a wretchedly small scale"
- Gordon's hierarchy of causes (ranked): (1) urban sanitation infrastructure — clean water may explain 75% of infant mortality decline; (2) uncontaminated milk, food regulation; (3) Pasteur germ theory → behavioral change; (4) window screens; (5) horse-to-automobile transition removing manure; (6) improved surgery (anesthetics, antiseptics); (7) basic medical tools — ECG, X-ray
- American "negative exceptionalism": American cities installed water and sewer pipes 2–3 decades LATER than large western European cities; political system still unable to adopt universal health insurance
- Gordon's indictment: "Why should households suffering from the devastating loss of income through unemployment also lose their access to what should be a universal right, the ability to obtain health care services... Bismarck figured out this greatest of all economic policy issues in the 1880s, but even now an efficient system of the provision of medical care as a right of citizenship has thus far eluded the American political system"

---

### Chapter 8: Working Conditions on the Job and at Home

**Chapter Overview**
- Opening epigraph from Harvey Green (2000): farm, sea, factory, forest, mine workers all faced "ever present possibility of injury, either immediate and possibly fatal, or the gradual, insidious work-linked lung and other diseases"
- 1870: >80% of labor force in hazardous, tedious, unpleasant jobs
- Standard 60-hour work week in 1900 → typical 40-hour week after 1940
- Three major trends: (1) rise of women's labor force participation, (2) rise of education / end of child labor, (3) invention of retirement

**Labor Force Participation Changes**
- Adult women (ages 25–64): participation rose gradually from 12% (1870) to 26% (1940), then surged from 32% (1950) to 72% (2000)
- Female participation rate increased 2.2 percentage points per decade 1880–1940 vs. 6.5 points per decade 1940–2010
- Only decade female participation declined: 1910–1920
- Adult males (ages 25–64): held steady at >95% throughout 1870–1940; began accelerated decline after 1970
- Teenage boys (ages 10–15): 30% in labor force in 1880; boys 14–15: a startling 50% in labor force
- Child labor statistics exclude unpaid farm work — actual participation far higher
- Boys 14–15 participation: declined from 42% in 1910 to 10% in 1940 — coincides with high school expansion
- Girls 14–15: peaked at 20% (1910), declined to 4% (1940); though lower market participation, girls engaged in heavy home production (laundry, cooking, childcare, making clothing for family)
- Elderly males (65–74): 88% participation in 1870 → 53% in 1940 → 24% in 1990
- Elderly males had no choice pre-Social Security: "they worked until they dropped"
- Elderly female participation: flat at ~10% throughout 1870–2010
- Invention of retirement preceded Social Security: decline in elderly male participation had begun well before the New Deal

---

## Pages 301–320

### Chapter 8 (continued): Working Conditions — Occupational Shifts, Hours, Farms, Industry

**The Decline of Disagreeable Work**
- Share of workers in "unpleasant" jobs (farming + blue-collar + domestic service): 87.2% in 1870 → 21.6% in 2009
- Decline fairly steady at ~5 percentage points per decade; slowest during 1870–1910 (–3.2/decade), fastest during 1940–70 (–6.8/decade)
- Ratio of disagreeable to nonroutine cognitive jobs: 7.9 in 1870 → 2.1 in 1940 → 0.1 in 2010
- But classifications understate improvement — a 2009 farmer rides in GPS-guided, air-conditioned John Deere tractor with on-board computer, vs. 1870 farmer behind a horse in heat, rain, insects
- Three-way classification: (1) truly disagreeable (farming, laboring, domestic service), (2) repetitive/boring (craftsmen, operatives, service workers), (3) nonroutine cognitive (professional/managerial). The big shift 1870–1940 was from disagreeable to repetitive. Only after 1970 did shift become unambiguously positive toward nonroutine cognitive

**The Work Week: Fewer Hours**
- 1870: 10 hours/day, 6 days/week = 60 hours/week standard
- By 1920: 8 hours/day, 6 days → By 1940: 8 hours/day, 5 days = 40-hour week
- 40-hour week has remained stable for 70 years of the postwar period — "seven decades of stability after such radical change"
- John Maynard Keynes 1931 prediction that turned out quite wrong: "Three-hour shifts or a fifteen-hour week may put off the problem for a great while" (workers would only need 15 hrs/wk due to productivity)
- Series declines: 58.5 hours/week in 1890s → 41 hours after 1950
- Dora Costa survey of late 19th-century nonfarm workers: average 10.2 hours/day for men, 9.5 for women; 7 a.m. to 5:30 p.m. with 30-minute lunch; virtually all worked Saturday same hours as weekdays
- Class difference: bottom wage decile in 1890 worked 11 hours/day; top decile worked 9 hours
- Most of the work-week reduction happened 1900–1940; post-1940 progress minimal and counterproductive (involuntary part-time work to avoid benefits)
- April 2015: 6.6 million people in part-time jobs who preferred full-time work

**The American Farmer: Volatility, Isolation, Debt**
- Homestead Act 1862: 160 acres free to anyone who would occupy and improve it; 1862–1913: 2.5 million homestead claims; 4 million settlers filed claims to 270 million acres in 30 states (10% of U.S. area)
- Only ~40% of claims finalized: "Drought, insect plagues, low [farm] prices, and isolation caused thousands of farm sites to be abandoned"
- Heat: Kansas memoir reported 108°F in the shade; "winds were hot and dry and the grass, baked on the stem, had become as inflammable as hay"; women "began to complain bitterly of the loneliness and lack of shade"
- 1874: grasshopper plague ravaged crops from Dakotas to Texas
- Buffalo slaughter in 1870s → destruction of original ground cover → cattle/sheep grazing degraded further → by 1930s "virtually the entire Great Plains region suffered from moderate to severe sheet erosion and slight to severe wind erosion… the Mississippi River alone deposited 15 tons of sediment a second into the Gulf of Mexico"
- Startup costs: $981 for 40-acre farm to $3,013 for 160-acre farm when average annual wage was ~$400 → many farmers became tenants; 1900: 60% of farms at age 25 were tenant-operated
- Commodity price trap: good harvest → oversupply → lower prices; high prices → more planting farther west on less fertile land → more supply → prices down again; "Midwestern farmers lived on the edge in good times and bad"
- Farm hours: labor intensity forced farm families to have many children (needed at harvest time); 1880: 20 person-hours to harvest one acre of wheat → 1935: 6.1 person-hours (3x efficiency gain)
- 1940 California wheat farmer: "We no longer raise wheat here, we manufacture it…. We are not husbandmen, we are not farmers, we are producing a product to sell"
- Hybrid corn seeds by 1940: 24% nationwide, 77% in Iowa
- Cowboys: before refrigerated railway cars, cattle had to be driven to cities; cowboys were wage employees, not cattle owners; wages $25–$60/month for jumping horses into freezing streams, stopping stampedes in the dark, working "up to your ears" in mud
- Sharecropping in the south: 1880 tenancy rates — Midwest 19.2%, Deep South 43.1%; 1920 — Midwest 28.9%, Deep South 60.9%; for blacks in the south ~75% tenancy
- Sharecropping mechanics: landowner kept all crops until harvest; sharecropper got half the income; had to buy food and supplies on credit from owner → debts often exceeded crop value → sharecroppers became indentured servants in practice

**Mining and Industrial Working Conditions**
- Coal mining: deaths at 1–2 per day in late 19th century from roof collapses, runaway coal buggies, flooding, faulty explosives; 1930 injuries per hour worked almost 5x higher than manufacturing
- Black lung disease: coal dust permanently disables lungs; miners "become bent like a gnome"; in winter, miners could go an entire week without seeing daylight
- Slaughterhouse conditions: assembly line method developed in Chicago before Ford's auto factory; workers stood at same position all day doing same repetitive motion; didn't know when leaving home whether they'd be back at noon or 9 p.m.
- Steel mills: 12-hour days by 1880s, 1910 survey showed 72.6 average hours/week; two 12-hour shifts instead of three 8-hour; working conditions "insulting" — no lockers, insufficient washrooms lacking soap and toilet paper, no light bulbs in toilets (to discourage reading), mill workers with filth "spill into the streets" at shift end
- Steel price crash: $85 → $27 per ton between boom of 1880 and depressed market of 1885 → brutal cost-cutting; "pushers" (foremen) drove men to maximum output
- English steelmaker visiting America: "The bosses drive the men to an extent that the employers would never dream of attempting in this country"
- Eleanor Marx Aveling and her husband (1886): "American laborers started to work at an earlier age than their British counterparts, worked more strenuously, and died, on the average, almost a decade earlier"
- Electrification of manufacturing: Paul David — half of 1919–1929 manufacturing productivity surge from electric motor capacity; key benefit was also improvement in working conditions — "lighter, cleaner workshops were made possible by the introduction of skylights" and elimination of overhead shafts and belting that "swirled dust and grease through the factory atmosphere" and "threatened to maim or kill workers"
- Industrial deaths, Pittsburgh 1900: 526 accidental deaths in a single county in 1907; death rate from industrial accidents in Pittsburgh nearly doubled from 123 to 214 per 100,000 between 1870 and 1900
- Lynd survey (1925): 1 in 5 workers had accident serious enough to cause income-losing absence in 1923; 29% lost 3+ weeks; death rate 50 per 100,000 workers
- Iron and steel: "Molten metal spattered the millhands. Unstable piles of iron billets stood everywhere. Hot floors burned feet through wooden-soled shoes. Molds and furnaces exploded. The machinery had no protective guards"
- No legal protection for injured workers: courts ruled workers "assumed the risk" by accepting employment in steel, coal, railroads

---

## Pages 321–340

### Chapter 8 (continued): Triangle Shirtwaist, Wages, Child Labor, Education

**Triangle Shirtwaist and Female Working Conditions**
- Triangle Shirtwaist Factory fire, NYC, March 1911: 148 employees died — mostly young immigrant women
- Workers were locked in rooms; "Scores of charred bodies were found piled against closed doors. They had been kept bolted, a newspaper reported, to safeguard employers from the loss of goods by the departure of workers" — directly parallel to Bangladesh factory fires of 2012–13
- Female workers in apparel: unskilled, unorganized, crowded into few occupations with low wages
- Firms preferred women: "docile, cared most about their families, had little expectation of advancement, and posed no likelihood of joining a trade union"
- Machinery reduced physical demands → firms found women could do the same work at lower pay; shoe factories: female share rose from 5% (1870) to 25% (1910)
- Pre-sewing-machine conditions: "I have worked from dawn to sundown, not stopping to get one mouthful of food, for twenty-five cents. I have lived on one cracker a day when I could not find work … made shirts for eight cents apiece and by working early and late could make three in a day"
- "Marriage brings a woman a life sentence of hard labor in her home. Her work is the most monotonous in the world and she has no escape from it"
- Female home production hours (ages 25-54): 50.4 hours/week in 1900 → 31.1 in 2005; male home production: 3.7 hours/week in 1900 → 17.3 in 2005
- Ruth Schwartz Cowan paradox: consumer appliances didn't reduce overall home production hours — rising standards (cleaner houses, better meals) absorbed the time savings
- Lynd survey 1925: 120 working-class wives worked 4–7 hours/day at home; "People are more particular about diet today. They care more about having things nicely served and dressing for dinner"
- 1940 housing snapshot: 33% of homes still cooked with wood/coal; 20% lacked electric light; 30% lacked running water; 40% lacked indoor toilet; 44% lacked private shower/bathtub; 58% lacked central heating

**Business Cycle and Income Instability**
- Severe depressions: 1873–78, 1893–97; shorter downturns mid-1880s and after 1907 crisis
- Between 1907 panic and mid-1909: half of 40,000 blast furnace workers in steel lost their jobs
- 1880 (prosperous year): 30% of all Pittsburgh working-class men experienced unemployment lasting longer than a month
- Workers sometimes reported for work only to find plant closed; no advance notification, no severance pay
- Before New Deal: unemployed workers had only their savings and private charity; middle/upper classes had no sympathy — portrayed workers as "dullards or as dangerous, drunken louts"
- Workers' compensation legislation: all but 4 of 48 states had passed WC laws by 1910–1920

**Real Wages vs. Productivity**
- 1870–1940: real wages grew FASTER than productivity — 2.48% vs. 1.51% per year annually
- 1940–present: reversed — productivity (2.25%/yr) outpaces real wages (1.56%/yr) by 0.69 percentage points
- Fastest real wage growth: 1910–1940 at 3.08%/year — a full percentage point faster than 1870–1910
- Explanation for pre-1940 fast wage growth: end of mass immigration (WWI + restrictive quotas of 1921/1924/1929) removed the "unlimited supply" that had held wages down; New Deal encouraged unions → 4.64%/yr wage growth 1936–40
- Henry Ford's $5/day (January 1914): doubled the standard manufacturing wage of $2.04/day; ulterior motive was to reduce labor turnover — mine superintendent alleged hiring 5,000 workers in one year to maintain 1,000-person workforce
- Ford's paternalism: 200 "Sociological Department" agents visited all 13,000 employees' homes; required workers to be married; provided doctors and nurses; helped workers buy homes; but fired 100 workers for celebrating Eastern Orthodox Christmas
- Post-1980 divergence: large share of productivity gains going to top 1% — consistent with rising inequality literature
- Pittsburgh 1906 wage study: 2:1 ratio between most skilled (bricklayers) and least skilled (common laborers)
- Two worlds of Pittsburgh manual workers: at top — "high-skilled, high-income workers able to purchase their own homes, to wash in indoor bathrooms… able to enjoy the 'American standard'"; at base — "crowded into hastily converted tenements… sharing outside toilet facilities and a communal faucet… workers to whom leisure was sleep"

**Child Labor and Education**
- Boys 14–15 participation in labor force: 50% in 1870; declined to 10% by 1940 as high school expanded
- "Breaker boys" (ages 8+) in coal mines picked through mined coal and threw out slag; "trappers" opened and closed underground doors; boys paid half of adult wages (75¢ to $1.25/day)
- Boys and women paid roughly half the hourly rate of adult men
- Girls: children of textile workers — 76% in northeastern textile workers' families, 94% in southern states went immediately from school to mill
- High school graduation rates 1876: only 20,000 graduates per year in population of 45 million (ratio of HS to elementary attendance: 6%)
- "Education belt": highest high school graduation rates in Iowa, Indiana, Nebraska — all north central states ranked higher than any mid-Atlantic states; in 1910, NY and NJ in same category as former Confederate states
- HS graduation rates: 9% (1910) → 51% (1940) → 76.9% (1970); grew by 14 percentage points per decade 1910–1940, then 8.7 per decade 1940–1970, zero after 1970
- "The opportunity cost of extra education" was highest in urban manufacturing centers; lowest in farm communities (seasonal attendance allowed)
- Small-town boys had much more leisure: Sinclair Lewis's nostalgia for "swimming and fishing in Sauk Lake… tramping the woods looking for excitement. Country roads beckoned the town boy to fish, to hunt"

**Chapter 8 Conclusion**
- Three dimensions of declining work disutility: (1) fewer hours per week (60→40); (2) occupational shift away from backbreaking/dangerous work; (3) improvement in conditions within each occupation
- Gordon's moral indictment: Carnegie remembered "benignly for his contributions to museums and public libraries" while his workers endured 12-hour days in heat and danger without lockers or working toilets
- "No other era in human history, either before or since, combined so many elements in which the standard of living increased as quickly and in which the human condition was transformed so completely"

---

## Pages 341–360

### Chapter 9: Taking and Mitigating Risks — Consumer Credit, Insurance, and Government

**Consumer Credit: Older Than We Think**
- Consumer credit was NOT invented in the 1920s — it was pervasive in rural America from the beginning
- Farmers bought goods on credit at general stores, repaid at harvest; horse, cart, harness, furniture purchased on 50% cash + bill
- Low default rates: nonpayment meant loss of credit in tight-knit communities; "payment of debts was a virtue and inability to pay them a mortal sin"
- U.S. developed credit earlier than Europe: American farmer owned his own land (vs. European tenant farmers); in U.S. the borrower bore the social stigma ("penniless failure"), not the lender
- Traveling salesmen provided credit to isolated farms; finance traced back to Chicago or New York; "Everyone owed money to everyone else, and for much of the year the only way to sell anything at all was to do so 'on time'"
- Sharecroppers: interest rates 40–60%; debt peonage — unpaid debts from harvest shortfalls accumulated year after year; sharecroppers often couldn't leave without voiding debt obligations
- Southern crop-lien system: harvested crop brought to lienholder who paid off farmer's debts; rural crossroads merchant had local monopoly; also profited as crop broker
- Coal miners: company store debts deducted from paychecks, tied workers to overpriced purchases, prevented mobility
- Urban pawnbrokers: medieval origins; weekly cycle of pledging and redemption tracked paychecks and rent payments; seasonal pledging of winter clothes in spring for fall redemption; regulated by late 19th century (interest rate limits, police registration)

**The Installment Plan**
- Modern consumer credit began 1845 with installment sales of pianos and organs; 1850: Singer Sewing Machine offered machines at $1 down and 50¢/week
- "Chattel lending": collateral was legal title, not the object itself — allowed confidentiality; by 1870s even working-class immigrants could buy on installment
- "Wage assignment" loans (ancestor of payday loans): collateral was future wages; lenders favored stable government/clerical workers; collection via social stigma before legal garnishment
- Loan sharks: "How can men be so reckless as to borrow from these agencies that are everywhere known as sharks, leeches, and remorseless extortioners?" — trapped borrowers in usurious cycles with police corruption facilitating violence
- U-shaped transition: early credit-dominant (rural) → cash-based 1890–1920 (A&P went cash-only 1910–12; Sears all-cash by 1902; "We do not accept revenue stamps, foreign stamps and due stamps, as they are of no value to us") → back to credit in 1920s
- By 1929: installment credit financed 61% of new cars, 65% of used cars; 80–90% of furniture, 75% of washing machines, 65% of vacuums, 75% of radio sets, 80% of phonographs
- Car loan effective interest rates in 1920s: typically 34% (Martha Olney)
- GMAC (General Motors Acceptance Corporation) established 1919 — beginning of modern auto finance; Ford opposed installment buying but by 1919 two-thirds of Fords sold on installment via local finance companies
- Marshall Field's credit accounts in Chicago: 180,000 by 1929, double the 1920 number; most large department stores had 50–70% of sales on credit by the 1920s
- Gordon's critique: the "durable goods boom" of the 1920s may have been driven more by newly invented products (electric refrigerators, cars) than by consumer credit expansion — credit ratio rose while consumer durables share of GDP barely budged
- Consumer debt added to Great Depression collapse: overlevered households had to deleverage when income/jobs were cut in 1929–30

**Mortgage Finance and the 1920s Housing Boom**
- First installment loan: Harrison Act of 1800 — government sold public land on 25% down + 4-year repayment; 19.4 million acres sold 1800–1820
- 1890 census: 29% of U.S. homes had outstanding mortgages; typical Boston area home required saving 50% of purchase price + 40% first mortgage + second mortgage
- Loans typically ran 3–8 years; principal due in lump sum at maturity (until amortized loans became standard in 1920s)
- Building and loan associations pioneered amortized mortgages (monthly principal + interest payments) — valuable innovation reducing risk for both parties
- Lynds' Muncie, Indiana: in 1890s most houses built for rental; by 1923, only 10% rental; 75–80% of new homes by mid-1920s sold to owners (85% to "working men") through building & loan associations
- Mortgage debt soared: from ~$12B in 1919 to $43B in 1930 (16% → 41% of nominal GDP)
- Real estate mortgage bond: facilitated the massive and unsustainable 1920s apartment building boom; by early 1930s roughly $10 billion outstanding
- Homeownership near 50% nationwide by 1930
- Depression: mortgage debt/wealth ratio spiked when values collapsed; bank failures decimated mortgage finance; near zero new construction through WWII

**Life Insurance: The Oldest Financial Institution**
- 900 BC Rhodes sea law: contributions from community covered ship/cargo losses — prototype of insurance
- 1550s London "Lombard Street" (from Italian province Lombardy): first modern insurance
- First formal life insurance policy: 1583, William Gibbons of London — also first policy taken to court for settlement
- First U.S. term life insurance: 1759, for Presbyterian ministers in Philadelphia
- Pre–Civil War: policies had no cash or loan values; simple coverage documents
- 1870–1900: transformed to modern form with agents on commission selling cash/loan value policies
- By 1900: life insurance = "method of forced saving" — "Nothing so far has been devised which enables so large a proportion of persons to save under such easy conditions as life insurance"
- Life insurance company assets as % of GDP: 4.5% (1875) → 10.4% (1905) → 14.5% (1914) → 16.9% (1929) → 37.0% (1933, due to deflation) before declining
- 1915: ~25–30% of population had life insurance (roughly universal for adult males)
- 1915 premiums: 2.8% of GDP; 2.1% returned as death benefits
- 1926: insurance in force = $79B = 81% of GDP; 6x the insurance company assets of $12.9B
- Policy loans in 1915 = 15% of insurance company assets — provided cash to tide families over unemployment/slack work; also used for home down payments

---

## Pages 361–380

### Chapter 9 (continued): Insurance, Government, and Chapter 9 Conclusion; Entr'acte

**Life Insurance Agents and Fraternal Insurance**
- 20% of all life insurance premiums collected by agents making weekly home visits — not just to collect premiums but pay dividends, prepare death proofs, even pay claims
- Life insurance companies self-interestedly distributed millions of health pamphlets (tuberculosis, care of children, milk purity, "flies and filth"); some provided free medical exams and nurse visits — analogous to Ford's Sociological Department
- Fraternal insurance (first offered 1868): by 1915 represented 1/3 of all life insurance in force
- Fraternal plans' fatal flaw: enrolled young, healthy members at cheap rates but failed to build assets for aging member deaths; NY State 1915 — fraternal orders held only 2% of assets vs. coverage; commercial companies held 28%
- Fraternal share fell from 33% to 15% between 1915 and 1925 as plans failed or imposed drastic rate increases

**Fire and Automobile Insurance**
- U.S. fire death rates among highest in developed world even today: 26.4 per million (1979–92) vs. 5.2 Switzerland, 6.4 Netherlands
- Fire insurance originated in England after London's Great Fire of 1666 (three-quarters of buildings destroyed)
- Philadelphia 1752: first U.S. fire insurance company (Philadelphia Contributionship); seven "fire extinguishing companies" already existed
- Great Chicago Fire 1871: 49% of destroyed building value was insured; 51 small insurance companies put out of business; most claims eventually paid; Chicago rebuilt immediately using land value as loan collateral
- San Francisco earthquake/fire 1906: damage 2.0–2.5x Chicago's; same ~50% insurance coverage; >80% of insurance claims paid
- First automobile insurance policy: 1897; compulsory insurance began with Connecticut in 1925; some states waited until late 1940s/early 1950s
- State Farm (1922): founded by Illinois farmer George Mecherle, offended that insurers charged city and farm customers same rates; started as mutual company owned by policyholders
- Allstate (1931): founded by Sears CEO to complement tire/battery/accessories sales; agents located inside Sears stores; became fully independent stockholder-owned company in 1995

**Government's Role in Promoting Growth and Mitigating Risk**
- Common description of late 19th century as "laissez-faire" is misleading — government intervened extensively
- Key interventions: Homestead Acts, railroad land grants, food/drug regulation (1906), Prohibition (1920–33), land-grant universities, agricultural research stations, patent system, New Deal (FDIC, Social Security, unemployment insurance)
- Homestead Acts controversy: government granted land to railroads first (7% of U.S. continental area between 1850–70); homesteaders forced to inferior land outside railroad grants → many became tenants renting better railroad-owned land
- Morrill Act of 1862: land-grant colleges in every state and territory; second Morrill Act (1890) created HBCUs; by 1980 land-grant universities = 18% of U.S. college students, 66% of annual PhDs
- Agricultural Extension Service: fundamental research on soil fertility, crop varieties, plant disease control; 6 million individual farms in 1929 served by government-funded agents in every agricultural county; demonstrations in 56,000 rural communities
- Patent office: "fair, respected, impartial, and not subject to bribes or corruption"; provided strong protection at modest cost
- 1887 Interstate Commerce Act: created ICC to regulate railroad rates
- Sherman Antitrust Act (1890) led to 1911 Supreme Court breakup of Standard Oil trust
- Herbert Hoover as Commerce Secretary (1921–29): standardized sizes of nuts, bolts, auto tires, plumbing parts — a little-known factor enabling Arsenal of Democracy in WWII
- Prohibition assessment: alcohol expenditures as share of GDP did NOT decrease — decreased consumption offset by higher prices; productivity not enhanced; federal alcohol tax revenue lost, requiring higher income taxes mainly on the rich
- New Deal risk mitigation: FDIC nearly eliminated bank failures (10,000 of 25,000 banks had failed 1931–33); Social Security 1935; unemployment benefits adopted by all states by 1938 (covered 40–50% of prior wage, initially 16 weeks, later 26 weeks)
- Rural Electrification Administration (REA): Wyoming ranch woman called the day electricity arrived "my Day of Days because lights shone where lights had never been, the electric stove radiated heat, the washer turned, and an electric pump freed me from hauling water. The old hand pump is buried under six feet of snow, let it stay there! Good bye Old Toilet on the Hill!"
- WPA at peak 1938: 3 million jobs (7% of labor force); built many U.S. post offices
- CCC: hired mainly young men (max 330,000); planted trees, improved national parks
- Michael Darby: official 1941 unemployment rate of 9.9% was actually 6.6% when WPA/CCC workers counted as employed

---

### Entr'acte: The Midcentury Shift from Revolution to Evolution

**Three Industrial Revolutions**
- IR #1 (steam engine + railroads + iron/steel): inventions 1770–1820, effects throughout 19th century
- IR #2 (electricity + internal combustion engine): inventions late 19th century, maximum effect 1920–70
- IR #3 (information and communication technology): began 1960, continues today
- Critical distinction: IR #2 covered virtually the ENTIRE span of human wants — food, clothing, housing, transportation, entertainment, communication, information, health, medicine, working conditions; IR #3 revolutionized only entertainment, communications, and information
- "This single fact, the narrowness of the effects of IR #3, is enough to explain why growth in output per person and output per hour began to slow down after 1970"
- TFP growth pattern: speedup in 1920–70; post-1970 growth barely a third of 1920–70 rate

**What Real GDP Misses (Gordon's Litany)**
- Standard of living tripled 1870–1940: real GDP per person grew from $2,770 to $9,590 (2009 dollars)
- Real GDP DOES NOT VALUE:
  - Brightness and safety of electric light vs. kerosene/whale oil danger
  - Increased food variety — processed foods, fresh meat via refrigerated rail cars
  - Department store invention — convenience and economies of scale
  - Mail-order catalogs — multifold increase in selection for rural population at lower prices
  - Removal of horse droppings from city streets
  - Motor vehicle's increased speed and load capacity; creation of "personal travel" industry
  - 80% price drop of Model T between 1910 and 1923 (car not in CPI until 1935)
  - Instant telegraph, telephone voice communication, phonograph music reproduction, radio entertainment
  - The difference between a nickelodeon with silent images vs. Gone With the Wind with color and sound at 23 cents average price
  - Reduction of infant mortality from 22% of births (1890) to 1% (1950) — by some estimates, this change created more welfare value than all other sources of consumer welfare increase combined
  - The change from 72-hour weekly steel mill work "accompanied by heat, sweat, and danger" to 40-hour week in an air-conditioned office

---

## Pages 381–400

### Entr'acte (continued) and Chapter 10: Post-1940 Food, Clothing, and Housing

**The Entr'acte's Quantitative Punchline**
- Understatement of 1870–1940 welfare gains: estimated consumer surplus values — railroads vs. canals: 3% of real GDP/year; tractors: 6% of real GDP/year; motion pictures through 1938: 3% of real GDP/year. "It is not difficult to imagine an omitted value to economic growth amounting to 100 percent of GDP"
- "Slowing evolutionary growth" post-1970: productivity growth averaged 2.72%/yr during 1953–64; slowed to 1.44%/yr during 1977–94; revived to 2.05%/yr during 1995–2004 (ICT wave); then collapsed to 1.30%/yr during 2005–2014 and reached only 0.6%/yr by end of 2014
- Hours per person: fell 1953–75, rose 1975–98 (women entering labor force), fell again after 1998 (female entry abated + baby boomers retiring post-2008)
- 2013–14: trend output per person growth = ZERO — labor productivity growth of 0.6%/yr exactly offset by negative hours per person growth
- The counterfactual: if productivity growth 1970–2014 had matched 1920–1970 rates, real GDP per person in 2014 would be $97,300 instead of actual $50,600 — a $46,700 difference for every man, woman, and child in the U.S.
- Pre-1968: trend growth in output per person ABOVE historical 2.1%/yr average; post-1968: consistently below

---

### Chapter 10: Fast Food, Synthetic Fibers, and Split-Level Subdivisions — Food, Clothing, Housing

**The Fundamental Contrast with Part I**
- Part I (1870–1940): every dimension of life experienced fundamental and revolutionary change
- Part II (1940–2015): pace of change varies widely; food and clothing show very little progress; housing shows rapid improvement 1940–70 then slowing

**Food by 1940: Already Modern**
- By 1940, food and its marketing were much closer to 2015 conditions than to 1870 conditions
- Prohibition (1920–33) and Great Depression distort any "normal" consumption for two decades before 1940
- Overall meat consumption fell by 1/3 between 1870 and 1940 (immigrants preferred stews, goulashes, Italian pasta dishes; disdained bland American bread)
- American vegetable diets were limited in 1920s: only potatoes, cabbages, lettuce, tomatoes, onions, corn, sweet potatoes, string beans in wide use
- Sales of citrus fruit tripled between 1920 and 1940 as immigrants' food habits spread to native-born population

**Self-Service Supermarket Revolution**
- Clarence Saunders, founder of Piggly-Wiggly, opened first self-service market in 1916
- Conversion concentrated in 1930s; halted by ban on new construction during WWII
- "Supermarket" term first used in 1933; late 1920s self-service markets up to 10,000 sq ft (vs. 600 sq ft for typical A&P chain store)
- First shopping cart introduced 1937; A&P forced to close more than half its stores 1936–41
- Supermarket share of total food sales: 28% (1946) → 48% (1954) → 69% (1963)
- Two central innovations: (1) all food items under one roof; (2) separation of selection from payment

**Frozen Food**
- Freezing technique perfected by Clarence Birdseye in 1926; marketing of frozen food began March 1930
- Initially slow — 1930s refrigerators had no separate freezers; two-temperature refrigerators not sold until 1939
- TV dinners and frozen vegetables became everyday staples by 1950s
- 1954 magazine editor imagined frozen food would "emancipate women from any need to cook" — predictions proved overblown
- Frozen food remained a small fraction of total consumption

**Wartime Food Rationing**
- 1942–45: sugar, fats, meats, canned fruits and vegetables all rationed; coffee rationed to conserve ocean shipping
- Every American received a ration book with coupons; Victory Gardens; home canning averaged 165 jars per year by 3/4 of families
- Red meat rationed but fish and poultry not → harbinger of long-term shift toward poultry

**Postwar Food Patterns**
- Meat composition shifted dramatically: poultry-to-red-meat ratio was 14% in 1940 → 89% by 2010
- By 2010, annual food consumption = 1,563 lbs/person (4.3 lbs/day) vs. 3.7 lbs/day in 1940 — rise in obesity as by-product
- Butter-to-margarine ratio: 7.0 in 1940 → 0.5 in 2010 (wartime butter shortage boosted margarine permanently)
- Fresh fruit consumption actually declined vs. 1940 — shift to processed juice largely complete by 1970
- Flour and cereal: declined 1940–70, then bounced back to 1940 level by 2010 (cold breakfast cereals)
- Food eaten away from home as share of food at home: 20% (1929) → 37% (1970) → 70% (2013); pace of shift slowed markedly after 1990
- Relative price of food eaten at home: virtually unchanged; relative price of food away from home: steadily rising (Baumol's cost disease — labor cost rises, food cost flat)

---

## Pages 401–420

### Chapter 10 (continued): Food Marketing, Obesity, Clothing, Housing, Appliances

**Food Retailing Evolution**
- Supermarket items stocked: 300–600 in 1920s chain stores → 2,200 by 1950 → 17,500 by 1985
- Post-1980: homogeneous supermarket chains challenged from below by Walmart/Costco (lower prices) and convenience stores, from above by Trader Joe's/Whole Foods
- Barcode scanning: invented in the 1980s; transformed checkout — previous clerks memorized all produce prices
- Walmart effect: lowers retail food prices by 25%; CPI fails to count this as a price decrease (outlet substitution bias — CPI only compares items at the same outlets); low-income consumers experience lower inflation than upper-income consumers
- 70% of fast food industry revenue comes from drive-through lanes — "assembly-line efficiency worthy of Henry Ford"
- Fast food primary tools for rapid delivery developed in the 1990s, not the past decade — evidence of slowing innovation

**Obesity**
- After century of stability (1870–1970), total daily calorie consumption increased >20% after 1970
- 1/3 of U.S. adults and 1/5 of children are obese
- 2000 obesity rates: U.S. 27%; no other of 23 countries exceeded 20%; Italy 8%, France 6%, Japan 2%
- Calories from fats/oils (not sugar) account for majority of increase; most extra calories consumed away from home
- Fast food drink sizes escalated from 8 oz to 16 or 32 oz; standard casual dining plate = 1,500–2,000 calories
- Gordon's conclusion: "Poor children sit in idleness in front of TV screens and eat cheap fast foods high in fats and cholesterol. Upper-middle-class children eat kale salads before their trip to participate on the soccer team" — obesity is a social/inequality problem, not a technology problem
- South Korean teens even more obsessed with video games than Americans — yet South Korea is not obese
- Warning: childhood obesity may cause "first such reversal in lifespan in modern history"

**Clothing: Minimal Change Post-1940**
- Clothing share of total consumer expenditures: 13.1% (1900) → 10.1% (1940) → 3.1% (2013)
- Relative price of clothing declined 1.5%/year over 1940–2012; accelerated to 2.6%/year after 1980 due to imports
- Near total replacement of domestic clothing by imports post-1980; 650,000 apparel jobs disappeared 1997–2007
- 2013 U.S. apparel imports: 49.1% cotton, 48.8% polyester/manmade, 2.1% wool/silk
- Synthetic fabrics are the only genuine quality improvement — eliminated ironing
- Shift from formal to casual; women: dresses → pants; men: suits → business casual; jeans became universal unisex by mid-1970s

**Housing: From Levittown to McMansions**
- By 1940: urban housing fully networked with electricity, gas, telephone, running water, sewers
- Modern conveniences reached 100% coverage: electric power by 1950; running water/exclusive flush toilet by 1970; central air conditioning from 37% (1970) to 89% (2010)
- Housing starts: 1920s peak at 186% of 1929 level in 1923–27 → collapsed to 31% in 1931–35; postwar peak 146% in 1950–54; 2009–13 = 30% (lower than Depression)
- Median new single-family home: 1,900 sq ft (1990) → 2,364 sq ft (2013); more than doubled since postwar
- 1992–2013: homes with 4+ bedrooms: 29% → 44%; 3+ bathrooms: 14% → 33%; 3+ car garage: 11% → 21%
- Nixon–Khrushchev "Kitchen Debate" (1959, Moscow): Soviet journalists called American kitchen exhibit a "Taj Mahal" only millionaires could afford; Nixon: $100/month mortgage within reach of a steel worker
- Family room: postwar invention centered on TV; became "great room" combining kitchen and living space — ironically a throwback to the 1870 farmhouse's central all-purpose kitchen

**Household Appliances**
- Refrigerators: 44% of homes (1940) → 98% by 1960; washing machines never reached same penetration (apartment communal laundry)
- Microwave oven: 8% of homes (1980) → 96% (2010) — fastest appliance adoption in postwar history
- Dishwasher/garbage disposal: only 60% by 2010
- Early refrigerators quality poor: "Food kept for any length of time in them tended to dry out. Ice accumulated relentlessly around the freezing elements, demanding frequent defrosting"
- By 1964: all tested refrigerator models finally held 0–5°F consistently
- Clothes dryer eliminated the tedious task of hanging clothes on outdoor lines

## Pages 441–460

### Chapter 11 (continued): Postwar Automobiles, Interstate Highways, and the Dawn of Jet Travel

**Contours of Change in Postwar Travel**
- Urban transit: universal postwar replacement of streetcar by bus; some cities built new heavy rail (Atlanta, Washington, San Francisco) or light rail (Dallas, Denver)
- Motor vehicles per 100 households: 2 (1910) → 89 (1929) → 113 (1950) → 171 (1970) → 202 (1990) → 207 (2010)
- Great transformation to motorized society essentially over by 1970 — another metric marking early 1970s dividing line
- Shift from cars to light trucks after 1970 means truck registration must be included in household data

**Vehicle Miles and Slowing Growth**
- Vehicle miles per person: 1.3 (1900) → 422 (1919) → 1,623 (1929); annualized growth rate 1919–29 = 13.5%/year
- Growth rate: 6.2% (1929–50), 8.0% (1950–80), only 1.1% (1980–2012)
- Vehicle miles per person in 2012 were 6.4% lower than in 2004 — and no higher than in 1997
- Airline revenue passenger miles (RPMs) per person: 32%/year growth (1940–60), 16.5% (1960–80), 7.8% (1980–2000), 0.6% (2000–2013)
- Air traffic: tripled in 1950s, tripled again in 1960s, doubled in 1970s, almost doubled in 1980s — then slowed to crawl
- Railroad passenger miles per person peaked at 448 in 1919; fell to 32 by 2012; air surpassed rail as early as 1956

**Automobile Quality: Postwar Era**
- Motor vehicle sales: 5.3 million (1929) → 7.9 million (1950) → 9.1 million (1955)
- Two-way virtuous circle: auto production fueled GDP growth → rising incomes enabled two-car families → more vehicle sales
- 1950s automobile status hierarchy: Cadillac/Lincoln/Chrysler Imperial (ancien régime wealth) → Buick Roadmaster (VP) → Buick Century (midlevel exec) → Oldsmobile → Pontiac → Chevrolet (unionized working class)
- Car quality measured differently from appliances: CPI officials obtained Detroit's estimates of value of each quality improvement (seat belts, heavier bumpers, etc.)
- Relative price of new motor vehicles fell by more than half 1960–2014; overall consumer prices rose factor of 7.6 but auto prices only factor of 4.1 between 1950–2013
- Average price of new car: $2,300 (1950) → $24,100 (2012) — 10x increase; but CPI only 4x, implying huge quality increase
- Implicit quality of cars (real inflation-adjusted price per car): grew at 2.3%/year (1950–70), 2.5% (1970–90), 3.2% (1990–2014)

**Accessories Becoming Standard Equipment**
- Automatic transmission: available on half of cars by 1953, more than 90% by 1970
- Air conditioning: 50% installation by 1970, 84% by 1983
- Power steering: 50% by 1965; power brakes: 50% by 1970; power windows: 38% by 1983
- Radios not standard until early 1960s

**Model T Affordability Paradox**
- 1923 Model T price: $265 = 11% of per-household consumption expenditures
- 1950 Plymouth: $1,520 = 33% of per-household consumption expenditures
- 2012 average vehicle: $24,000 = 21% of per-household consumption expenditures
- Model T was TWICE as affordable relative to incomes as today's typical motor vehicle — despite massive quality difference
- Model T: hand-cranked, only black, flimsy body, 20 horsepower; modern car: 14 times the quality of 1906 car

**CPI and Government-Mandated Equipment**
- Between 1967–85, CPI measured 56% quality increase in autos: 12% from safety, 25% from anti-pollution, 12% from other
- Anti-pollution equipment controversial: didn't raise quality for owner, reduced mpg; created positive externality for society, not owner — dubious to classify as quality improvement
- 1970 Clean Air Act dramatically reduced LA smog, but treating anti-pollution devices as auto quality improvement rather than government infrastructure spending remains questionable

**Fuel Economy, Safety, and Reliability**
- Fuel consumed over vehicle life costs as much as the vehicle itself; first 4 years alone = 40%+ of purchase price
- Average fuel economy: 15 mpg (1950) → 23.5 mpg (2012) = 56% improvement; economy declined 1950–70 as cars got bigger
- Cumulative quality factor from fuel economy 1967–2012 = 35%; total implicit quality factor 1950–2012 including fuel economy: 5.6x
- Combined 1906–2012 quality: 2.5x (pre-1940) × 5.6x (postwar) = 14x total quality improvement since 1906

**Safety: Fatalities per Mile**
- Fatalities per 100 million vehicle miles: peaked at 45 in 1909 → 1.1 in 2012
- Decline rate: –3.6%/year or –36%/decade for 103 years; most rapid decline 1909–26 (–6.2%/year)
- Interstates eliminated two-lane passing dangers; ratio of highway spending to GDP fell by half after 1972
- Oil change interval: every 1,000 miles (early postwar) → every 7,500 miles today
- Akerlof Nobel Prize partly for "The Market for Lemons" (1970) — auto reliability defects invisible to used-car buyers
- 1950s–60s car problems: oil leaks, exhaust smoke, engine overheating, A/C compressor failures
- 1984 Consumer Reports: 147 domestic models — 63 "much worse than average" black dots, only 1 red dot; 51 imports: 36 red dots
- Oil shocks 1974–75, 1979–81: oil $3 → $30+/barrel; gasoline $0.25 → $1.25+/gallon; import share: 4% (1963) → 42% (1987)

**The Interstate Highway System**
- Eisenhower 1919: Army expedition Washington D.C. to San Francisco by car — took 62 days
- As Supreme Allied Commander: saw German autobahns enable rapid troop movement; interstates were attempt to duplicate autobahn network across terrain 20x larger
- 1944 Federal Aid Highway Act: 40,000 miles designated; Marshall Plan, GI Bill, Korean War delayed implementation
- Highway Act of 1956: 41,000 miles, estimated $25 billion, completion planned 1969; 90% federal / 10% state
- Highway Trust Fund: gasoline tax revenues — efficiently allocated costs to users
- Pennsylvania Turnpike (1940): first model — 160 miles Harrisburg–Pittsburgh, cut through mountains, eliminated deadly passing situations
- Of 35 industries examined, all but 3 experienced significant cost reductions from interstates; interstate spending contributed ~31% productivity gain (1950s), ~25% (1960s), ~7% (1980s)
- Timeline: I-80 Nebraska first complete state (1974); I-5 Canada-to-Mexico (1979); I-80 coast-to-coast (1986); I-10 Jacksonville–Santa Monica (1990); final link (1992)
- Holiday Inn: 20 motels (1956) → 500+ (1963); drive-in culture: movies, restaurants, banks, churches, even funeral parlors — "Americans never wanted to leave their cars"
- Fraction of 16–24 year olds with driver's license: fell from 82% (1983) to 67% (2010); young people increasingly choosing urban centers

**Commercial Air Travel Beginnings**
- Air travel in 1940: passenger miles per person = same as automobile travel in 1904 (effectively infancy)
- 1926–1936: greatest decade of commercial aircraft advances in history; nothing after (except jet introduction 1958) comes close
- Since first jet flight 1958: NO improvement in speed or comfort; changes limited to electronic cockpit controls, fuel economy, minor range increase, in-flight entertainment
- Quality DECLINED in some ways: seating space substantially more cramped than 1958; much more time at airport before departure
- First U.S. commercial airline flight: April 6, 1926, Varney Air Lines (ancestor of United Airlines); Pasco, WA to Elko, NV (411 miles); Swallow biplane, room only for pilot and mail
- Walter Varney also founded Continental Airlines in 1934 (merged with United 2010) — both trace roots to same man

## Pages 461–480

### Chapter 11 (continued): Air Travel History, Deregulation, and Chapter 11 Conclusion

**Early Commercial Aviation Milestones**
- First commercial flight April 6, 1926: pilot Leon Cuddeback, 2,500 spectators at Pasco WA; balky engine refused to crank for 20 minutes; finally flew 411 miles to Elko NV
- 1931: Charles Lindbergh and Igor Sikorsky (Russian immigrant, later invented first viable helicopter in 1939) sketched the Sikorsky S-42 on a menu at an airport lounge
- S-42 flew first nonstop San Francisco–Honolulu service in 1935 (2,400 miles) — yet took 18 MORE years before a plane could fly the same 2,400-mile distance LA–NY
- 1935 first transpacific flight ceremony: 100,000 San Franciscans; CBS/NBC coast-to-coast radio; FDR letter: "Even at this distance I thrill to the wonder of it all"
- Flying boat advantage: took off from water, no airport construction needed on 1935 S-42 SF–Manila route (via Honolulu, Midway, Wake, Guam)
- Technical progression: 9-passenger 1929 Ford Trimotor → 14-passenger 1933 Boeing 247 (NY–Chicago 5.5 hrs with one fuel stop) → 21-passenger 1936 DC-3

**The Douglas DC-3: Best Aircraft in History**
- Jointly conceived by Donald Douglas and C.R. Smith (president of American Airlines); first flights June 26, 1936 simultaneous Newark–Chicago and Chicago–Newark
- DC-3 could carry 21 passengers (or 14 in sleeper beds); transcontinental in 15 hours with 3 fuel stops (leave LA after work, arrive NY for lunch next day)
- Round-trip sleeper fare: $285 in 1936 = $3,940 in today's prices — almost exactly the same as current business class fare of $3,600 NY–LA with lie-flat bed
- 1937 American Airlines timetable: "21-passenger Flagship Club Planes... air conditioned before departure... You arrive feeling as fresh and clean as when you left home"
- Round-trip price corrected for inflation: $1,182 (1937) vs. $1,185 (fastest train 1937) vs. $1,179 (comparable 2014 internet fare) — remarkable price continuity
- Speed comparison NY–Chicago: 3h55m in 1936 vs. 2h35m today — but in 1936 you arrived at airport 10 minutes before departure, no security, taxis waiting 5 minutes from gate; today arrive 1 hour early for security; total travel time 1936 vs. today: 3h50m vs. 3h50m — virtually identical!
- DC-3 production: 100/year 1936–41 (civilian); renamed C-47 Skytrain for WWII — 10,000 units produced (2,900/year); total production 10,600 by 1945
- DC-3s still in service: hundreds to thousands worldwide; popular in Africa (can land on dirt); lined up at San Juan PR airport daily for cargo among Caribbean islands; price: ~$100,000 used
- "The only replacement for a DC-3 is another DC-3" — legendary ruggedness

**Post-DC-3 Aircraft Progression**
- DC-6 (1946): 54 passengers, LA–Chicago 7.8 hours, pressurized cabin; DC-7 (1953): first nonstop LA–NY in 7.8 hours
- Boeing 707 jet (first flight late 1958): eliminated piston engine vibration; LA–NY in 4.8 hours; DC-8 competing jetliner (1959)
- Entire fleet converted to jets by late 1960s including 737s for short-haul routes by 1969
- REVERSAL: Today's LA–NY elapsed time = 5.6 hours, vs. 4.8 hours in 1958 (jets are SLOWER today due to fuel-saving speeds and runway congestion)
- Annual rate of elapsed time improvement: 8.7%/year (1934–36 to DC-3), 7.3%/year (to DC-6), 4.0%/year (to 707), then –0.2%/year since 1958 — NEGATIVE since jet era

**Air Safety**
- Air crash fatalities per 100 billion passenger miles: 580 (1950) → 10 by 1990 (–10.1%/year); then revolutionary improvement 1994–2006 (–23.2%/year)
- 2006–2014: only one U.S. event (49 deaths in 2009); otherwise ZERO fatalities for eight years — complete safety achieved in ~50 years
- Key accidents that drove improvements: Grand Canyon collision June 30, 1956 (TWA Super Constellation + United DC-7, 128 deaths) → created FAA 1958; American Airlines DC-10 crash Chicago O'Hare May 25, 1979 (271 dead, engine detached due to faulty maintenance); AA Airbus A300 crash Queens NY Nov 12, 2001 (pilot error, rudder caused tail to snap off)
- "Air travel was initially 'unsafe at any speed' but now is safer than walking across the street" (paraphrasing Nader)

**Airline Prices and Deregulation**
- Real price of air travel: fastest decline 1940–60 (–8.1%/year) BEFORE jets; slower 1960–80 (–2.8%/year); no decline at all 1980–2013 (–0.1%/year)
- Passenger miles growth mirrored price changes inversely: 20.5%/year (1940–50), 12.1%/year (1950–60), 9.3%/year (1960–80), 2.9%/year (1980–2013)
- Before 1978 deregulation: CAB controlled all routes and prices; all airlines charged same prices (by distance); ~30% of travel required connections, often changing airlines mid-trip
- Pacific Southwest Airlines (PSA): first deregulation poster child — dominated intrastate California routes (162 nonstop flights/day, 22,000 seats between NorCal–SoCal in 1972) free from CAB regulation
- Key academic paper by economist Theodore Keeler on PSA was primary argument for deregulation
- After 1978: routes opened up; connections no longer required airline changes; airlines had to dominate their hub cities → massive mergers 1986–90 (TWA absorbed Ozark; Northwest absorbed North Central; PSA itself absorbed by US Airways)
- Deregulation did NOT lower average prices — instead increased variance (lower for advance personal travel, higher for last-minute business travel); "yield management" systems maximized revenue extraction
- American AAdvantage frequent flyer program launched May 1, 1981; United launched May 4 (three days later); AAdvantage Gold elite tier invented 1984 with upgrade benefits

**The Decline of Air Travel Quality**
- American Airlines 2008: started charging $15 (now $25) to check a bag; second bag $35 extra
- Hot meals in economy class ended after 9/11/2001; now must pay $8 for sandwich
- A $400 round-trip in 2014 effectively costs $496 when add bag fees + food — unmeasured 24% price increase
- Seat pitch: 34 inches was standard before 1977; now costs $59 extra on United for same space
- Security theater: 200 million hours/year wasted in security (~600 million passengers × 20 minutes) = ~$8 billion annual waste; 9/11 issue was flimsy cockpit doors (fixed within days); pre-2001 X-ray system for guns/metals was sufficient
- First-class premium cabins now more luxurious than ever vs. economy crammed tighter — symbol of rising inequality: "those at the cheap end barely have room to open their copies of Thomas Piketty"
- Inflight Wi-Fi by 2014 but usage rates <10% — not worth the price charged

**Chapter 11 Conclusion**
- Motor vehicles per household: rapid growth to 1970, slow 1970–90, flat after 1990; vehicle miles per person actually declined 2000–2014
- Steady improvement in auto quality and safety after 1970; quality factor 14x vs. 1906 car
- Air quality improvements pre-1940 vs. post: government price indexes missed most pre-1940 automobile quality improvements; CPI treatment of post-1940 auto quality far more complete
- Early 1970s = transition point for BOTH automobiles and air travel from rapid to slower progress
- Interstate Highway System (1958–72) contributed to labor productivity growth by making truck drivers more productive; economy-wide TFP slowdown after 1972 at least partly reflects end of highway construction productivity bonus
- Physical experience of air travel unambiguously deteriorated since early 1970s: tighter seats, security lines, fees for bags/food
- Deregulation 1978 did NOT cause price declines — real driver of past price declines was development of larger/faster aircraft making pilots more productive; successive mergers have coalesced domestic air transport into 4 major carriers maximizing ancillary fee revenue

## Pages 481–500

### Chapter 12: Entertainment and Communications — From Milton Berle to the iPhone

**Chapter Overview**
- Post-1940 information/entertainment world dominated by single behemoth: television
- Unlike appliances and transportation where progress slowed after 1970, entertainment/communications continued to accelerate — smartphones/social media constitute acceleration, not deceleration
- Television did not arrive in vacuum: built on radio broadcasting structures, stars, and funding

**Early TV History**
- 1870s: Sir William Crooks developed cathode ray tube; Karl Ferdinand Braun (1897) created cathode-ray oscilloscope; Boris Rosing (St. Petersburg, ~1907) achieved weak images on Braun tube
- Two key inventors 1920s–30s: Vladimir Zworykin (Russian immigrant, worked for Westinghouse/RCA, developed iconoscope camera tube) and Philo T. Farnsworth (self-taught, Rigby Idaho, developed own version at cost of $1 million vs. RCA's $9 million)
- Farnsworth patented electronic TV at age 24 in 1930; courts sided with him against RCA's patent interference suit; won majority of numerous patent proceedings
- David Sarnoff (RCA VP) declared TV's birth at 1939 New York World's Fair: "It is with a feeling of humbleness that I come to this moment..."
- FCC approved commercial standards July 1, 1941: CBS became WCBW and NBC became WNBT, first two commercial TV channels; Pearl Harbor (December 1941) delayed TV's rise, giving radio 5 more years
- May 1942: War Production Board prohibited new TV station construction; NBC and CBS cut TV broadcasting until summer 1944

**WWII as Radio's Last Hurrah**
- 62 million Americans (nearly half the population) listened to FDR's "date which will live in infamy" speech December 8, 1941
- Radio obliterated time and distance: Edward R. Murrow's live coverage of Nazi bombing of London changed how Americans learned about world events
- Motion pictures boomed during WWII: 23% of recreational spending; summer 1946 "Film Industry's Fattest Six Months" — $1.7 billion box office, 90 million people/week (60% of population) attended

**Television's Golden Age**
- TV diffusion: 9% of households owned TV (1950) → 64.5% (1955) — fastest diffusion of any appliance or device in history (13 points/year; faster than smartphone post-2003 or tablet post-2010)
- By 1955: 97% of households within TV signal reception range; 90%+ ownership by early 1960s
- FCC "freeze" 1948–52 capped stations at 108 (16 of them in just NY, Chicago, and LA)
- Early TV social character: watching at taverns, neighbor's house TV parties; most popular reason for buying a set: sports (1/3 of respondents); 18% bought for children; 15% after watching at friends' house
- First coaxial cable 1946 connected NY, Philadelphia, DC for Joe Louis–Billy Conn boxing match; AT&T coast-to-coast coaxial system 1951 reached ~95% of TV sets
- Time zone problem: Pacific broadcasts were "fuzzy" (filmed off monitor for rebroadcast 3 hours later) until videotape recorder introduced 1957
- TV as social equalizer: African American quoted: "With television we're on the level with everyone else. Before television, radio provided the little bit of equality we were able to get"
- January 19, 1953: CBS broadcast Lucy having a baby — 68.8% of country's TV sets tuned in; half the entire population watched Mary Martin as "Peter Pan" two years later
- Milton Berle "Uncle Miltie": Texaco Star Theater so popular that Detroit reservoirs dropped sharply when show ended (everyone went to bathroom at once)
- Daily radio listening per home: 4.4 hours (1948) → 2.4 hours (1955); in TV homes: 1.9 hours radio but 4.9 hours TV
- By 2005: average household spent 8+ hours/day watching television; TV consumed nearly half of all free time

**TV's Political and Social Power**
- 1960 Nixon–Kennedy debate: Nixon refused makeup, "looked like death"; Kennedy bronzed and sharp; radio listeners split on who won; TV viewers overwhelmingly picked Kennedy; Kennedy's victory often attributed to TV effect
- March 7, 1965: Selma to Montgomery march; TV broadcast of police attacking peaceful protesters inspired national outrage → Voting Rights Act of 1965
- TV "was hailed as the ultimate communication experience" — national networks created paradox: private home as recreation center but highly public, communal experience

**Old Media in Television Age**
- Movie weekly attendance: 60%+ of population (1946) → under 25% by mid-1950s (level stable to present)
- Films released: ~500/year (1930s) → 369 (1950) → 232 (1954) → ~200/year (1960–70) — but surviving films were higher-budget
- Hollywood films migrated to TV: by 1975, movies made up 50%+ of network primetime; 80% of nonaffiliated stations; NBC paid $10 million in 1974 for two-night Godfather special
- Radio adaptation: survived as personal companion (car, pocket transistor, personal listening); car radios grew from 30% (1940) to 95% (1970) of cars; "Radio didn't die. It wasn't even sick. It just had to be psychoanalyzed"

**TV Quality Improvements and Price Declines**
- 1950: $350 for 9-inch black-and-white RCA table model + $50/year service contract; 2014: $418 for 40-inch HD LED color with theater surround sound and Internet connectivity
- Repairs: $50/year in 1940s → virtually zero after vacuum tubes replaced by solid-state electronics (early 1960s)
- Energy: black-and-white sets 250W (1948) → 60W (1981); color sets 350W (1964) → 110W (1981)
- Repair incidence: reduced by factor of 30 for B&W (1950–86); factor of 10 for color (1964–86)
- True annual price decline 1952–83: –4.3%/year vs. CPI's –1.0%/year — difference of –3.3%/year
- Total unmeasured consumer surplus 1952–83: 278% of what was spent on TV sets (nearly triple!)
- Additional 89% understatement 1983–99; total understatement 1952–99 = 525% (2.78 × 1.89)
- 1998: CPI adopted hedonic price index for TV sets — after that, virtually no gap between CPI and actual prices (–20.4%/year CPI decline for HD sets in decade ending 2014)
- Key insight: CPI understatement of consumer surplus from new products was much larger in early postwar decades than in recent years
- Screen size progression: 10 inches (1950) → 19 inches (1983) → 40 inches (2014); $1,000 in 2014 bought 60-inch HD set with 36x the viewing area of typical 1950 set
- Price declines: 19-inch sets –9.0%/year (1992–99); 27-inch –6.0%/year; 32-inch LCD –22.5%/year (2005–14)
- Color TV: 1964 introduction; by mid-1970s majority of Americans watching in color; HD TV: <15% of households (2007) → >70% (2012)

**Cable Television**
- Origins: men in small isolated towns erected antenna towers and ran cable wires to bring clear signals; subscription ~$2–3/month
- FCC heavily regulated early cable (CATV) over broadcasting piracy concerns
- Cable explosion in 1980s: wired cable homes almost tripled 1980–90 (20% → 56% of TV households)
- Network affiliate stations: dropped below 80% in 1982; down to 60.7% by 1987; networks' audience share cut in half 1986–99 (to under 30%)
- HBO and premium cable: movies without advertising 24 hours/day
- Despite satellite TV competition, cable providers raised prices at 3x the rate of overall inflation

## Pages 501–520

### Chapter 12 (continued): VCR, Music, Telecommunications, and Digital Revolution; Chapter 13 Introduction

**VCR and Home Video**
- VCR entered U.S. market late 1970s; households with VCR: 1% (1980) → 68.6% (1990) → 81% (1995)
- VCR shipments exceeded washing machine shipments in value by 1983
- VCR price: $1,200 (1978) → under $250 (1987) — –17%/year, fastest of any appliance for 9 years
- CPI didn't include VCR until 1987 — all price decline and quality improvement before then completely missed in GDP
- Prerecorded VHS tapes: up to $80 to buy; video rental stores emerged to provide affordable access
- VCR not introduced into CPI until 1987 — massive consumer surplus entirely missed

**Music Transitions**
- 1948: Columbia introduced 33⅓ LP vinyl record (long-playing); RCA countered with 45-rpm record
- LP: up to 30 minutes per side, vinyl (vs. shellac), finer grooves, longer playing time; 45: cheaper, youth market, vehicle for rock 'n' roll — "the ultimate adolescent artifact"
- Magnetic tape cassette (1960s): portable, 45 minutes per side, enabled tape-to-tape copying; democratized music (rap music emergence in late 1980s); Walkman made music personal on the go
- CD (1982): laser instead of grooves, up to 75 minutes, random song access, superior sound quality; CD outsold vinyl by 1988; outsold cassettes by 1991; peaked 2002 at 95% of sales
- Vinyl record sales fell 80% between 1978–88; then digital/iPod disruption

**Digital Music Era**
- MP3 format late 1990s: file-sharing and CD ripping provided enormous free music access
- iPod (2001): click wheel interface + iTunes integration; replaced portable CD player; personal library of hundreds of albums in pocket
- Spotify: 30 million songs, $10/month subscription (or free with ads) — streaming revolution

**Telecommunications**
- 1940: only 40% of homes had a telephone; long-distance required multiple operators using manual switchboards
- First automatic toll switch: Philadelphia 1943; real breakthrough: AT&T Direct Distance Dialing (1951) — caller dials 10 digits including area code
- First 10-digit DDD call: Mayor of Englewood NJ to Mayor of Alameda CA, November 10, 1951 — took 18 seconds; vs. 1915 coast-to-coast call that took 23 minutes with 5 operators
- Area code pattern: middle digit "0" or "1"; largest metros got lowest digits (NY 212, DC 202, LA 213, Chicago 312)
- Transistor (1948, Bell Labs — Walter Brattain, John Bardeen, team): key to both telecommunications automation and computers
- Long-distance price: NY–SF 3-minute call fell from $75+ (1939) to ~$3 (1981); NY–London from $240+ to under $6
- Daily toll calls per capita: rose 11x over this period; by 1990 93% of Americans had a telephone
- Cell phones: Motorola 8000 (1984) — "compared to a brick"; Wall Street (1987) depicted as status symbol
- Cell phone subscribers: ~5 million (1990, 2% of population) → ~110 million (2000, 39%); average monthly bill fell ~50%
- By 2010: 2.6 cell phones per household; by 2013: 91% of adults had one; residential phone share of spending fell from 75% (2001) to 37% (2009)
- Social impact: "Where are you?" became a normal question; social planning became spontaneous/real-time texting
- Smartphone (BlackBerry first in U.S. 2003): combined phone, music, email, web, GPS; 58% of adults had smartphone by January 2014
- iPhone App Store launched 2008 with 500 apps → 700,000+ apps; 30+ billion downloads; Twitter: 78% of U.S. monthly users access via mobile

**News Media Evolution**
- TV news initially showed footage days/weeks after the fact; gradually developed live on-site reporting
- Walter Cronkite: "deeply trusted by millions... even mentioned as a suitable candidate for vice-president"
- CBS 60 Minutes launched 1968: still top-10 rated after 47 years
- CNN: first 24-hour news channel, 1980; then MSNBC (left), Fox News (right) by 1990s
- Newspaper circulation per household: 1.4 (1949) → 0.8 (1980) → <0.4 (2010)
- Newspapers adapted: analysis, sports sections (20% of content by 1980s), human interest stories
- 2003–2012: online newspaper ad revenues nearly tripled, but overall revenues cut in half (print advertisers left faster)
- 2014 poll: 87% used TV for news in past week; 69% used laptops/computers; 61% used newspapers; 65% used radio

**Digital Media Summary**
- Entertainment/communications uniquely shows NO post-1970 slowdown — accelerating if anything
- DVDs (1995 in U.S.): DVD player ownership exceeded VCR by 2006; 87% of households by 2011
- DVR: as of Oct 2013, <50% of households had DVR; average 30 minutes/day of time-shifted TV watching
- Netflix: streaming began 2007; 30+ million subscribers by 2014; first drove Blockbuster into bankruptcy
- Home media table 2011: Cell phone 87.3%, DVD player 86.7%, PC 80.9%, Internet 77.1%, TV 98.9%
- E-books: 28% of adults reading e-books in 2013 (up from 17% two years earlier)
- For every dollar of GDP spending on TV sets 1952–1999, quality improvements delivered $5 of unmeasured benefits; since 1999 CPI hedonic methodology eliminated this gap

**Chapter 13 Introduction: Computers and Internet**
- Computer performance/price improvement continuous and exponential since 1960 — dwarfs any precedent in technology history
- Key insight: ICT hardware/software/Internet/phone = only 7% of total economy in 2014
- Even if ICT performance-to-price rose 20%/year, with zero progress in other 93%, overall growth = only 1.4%/year
- Computer technology more impressive than entertainment/communications in absolute advance, but limited GDP share means limited macro impact
- Mainframe computers from 1960s: first bank statements, phone bills, insurance policies; airline reservation systems automated 1960s–70s

## Pages 521–540

### Chapter 13 (continued): Computers and Internet

**Moore's Law and Computer Price/Performance**
- Cray-1 supercomputer (1976): 160 million floating-point operations/second, 8 megabytes memory, filled small room; Los Alamos bought it for $8.8 million ($36.9M in today's dollars)
- 2014 Walmart Lenovo laptop ($449): 750x memory, 1,000x speed of Cray-1 — performance/price improved 44%/year since 1976
- Computing power price: $8.8 million (Cray 1976) → $0.60 (equivalent computing in 2014)
- Moore's Law (Gordon Moore, Intel cofounder, 1965): transistors per chip double every 24 months = 34.7%/year growth
- Intel 4004 (1971): 3,500 transistors; Intel 15-core Xeon Ivy Bridge (2014): 4.31 billion transistors
- Actual Moore's Law pace: accelerated to 60.1%/year (1997–2006), then collapsed to 11.5%/year (2006–2014)
- Doubling interval: traditionally 24 months → 14 months during 1997–2006 "go-go period" → 6 years after 2006
- Hal Varian (Google chief economist): slowdown is demand-side — "no one needs a superfast chip on their desktop"
- Nordhaus estimate: cost per computation declined 37%/year (1945–80), 64%/year (after 1980)
- Understatement note: quality improvements from flash drives vs. floppy disks, USB vs. serial/parallel ports, shorter boot times, portability/weight reduction, color vs. monochrome screens all missed in standard measures
- ICT spending (2014): only 7% of GDP; even 20%/year performance gains × 7% share = only 1.4% GDP growth boost

**Mainframes and Early Business Computing**
- ENIAC (revealed Feb 15, 1946): 30 short tons, 1,800 sq ft, 175 kilowatts, "several miles of wires," 1,000x faster than previous methods; "when ENIAC was turned on, the lights in Philadelphia dimmed"
- American Airlines SABRE (1964): first fully electronic airline reservation system; 1,000+ terminals from two IBM 7090s; processed 83,000 daily phone calls — no punch cards
- Life insurance companies first major mainframe buyers: bought UNIVAC 1 in 1954–55; punched-card equipment already in use since 1930s
- IBM 801 Bank Proof Machine (1934): listed, separated, endorsed, and totaled checks — milestone in check clearing
- IBM 1401 (1960s banking): tellers located customer information and printed results within seconds; Pacific National Bank Seattle (Aug 1961): check processing speed 3/minute → 75/minute
- First credit card: Frank McNamara forgot wallet at business lunch 1949 → founded Diners Club with 27 restaurants; Bank Americard (1958) → became Visa (1976); VISANet 2012: 200 countries, 15,000 institutions, 2 billion cards, 68 billion transactions/year
- ATM invented by Donald Wetzel (former IBM engineer); banks initially resisted: "we want to deal face-to-face with people"
- Barcode UPC: first scan June 26, 1974 — 67-cent pack of Wrigley's Juicy Fruit gum in Sharon Buchan's hands; $133,000 scanner system in 1974; Business Week 1976: "The Supermarket Scanner That Failed"; by 1980: 90% of grocery products had UPC
- Xerox 914 photocopier (1959): 650-pound behemoth, 100,000 copies/month, tended to catch fire; Fortune called it "most successful product ever marketed in America measured by return on investment"
- Electronic calculator (1970): eliminated overnight both Marchant mechanical calculator and slide rule

**Personal Computer Revolution**
- Altair computer (1975): no keyboard or screen, only flashing lights; but MITS hired Paul Allen (WSU dropout) and Bill Gates (Harvard dropout) to adapt BASIC for it → they founded Microsoft in April 1975
- Steve Wozniak attended Homebrew Computer Club (California, 1975) → built Apple Computer I → Steve Jobs joined for sales
- IBM PC (1981): broke IBM tradition by using Intel 8088 chip and Microsoft OS; released specs publicly for independent developers; expected 250,000 sales in 5 years, sold 1 million in less than 4 years
- Lotus 1-2-3 (leading spreadsheet 1980s), WordPerfect (leading word processor, reached version 6.0 by 1992)
- Word processing: IBM MT/ST magnetic tape typewriter (1964) → Wang 1200 (connected to IBM Selectric) → Wang Office Information System (1976, with screen) → PCs eliminated all this

**Internet Revolution**
- ARPANET (1969): Pentagon's ARPA, 2 dozen engineers; first successful computer link UCLA–Stanford; 20+ nodes by 1971
- Early online services (Prodigy, CompuServe, AOL) in 1980s: slow, limited, rudimentary
- World Wide Web (Dec 1991): first U.S. server at Stanford Linear Accelerator; Mosaic browser (Sept 1993) = "killer app" of Internet
- Windows 95 launch (Aug 24, 1995): long lines waiting hours; Microsoft Internet Explorer included → transitional moment; excited observer: "The Internet is slow, superficial, chaotic, nerdy, hostile, and largely a waste of time. You just gotta try it."
- PC adoption: 13 years to reach 30% of households; Internet adoption: only 7 years to reach 30% (from Mosaic 1993); but both slower than TV (5 years from 5% to 65%)
- Broadband surpassed dial-up in 2005; dial-up now almost disappeared
- Social media adults: 8% (2005) → 72% (2013); teens/young adults ~90%; MySpace was leader in 2005, Facebook just 1 year old
- Wikipedia: 4.6 million English articles; full print version would require 2,052 volumes; 270 languages

**E-Commerce: Amazon Revolution**
- Amazon founded 1994; initially sold books; Borders declared bankruptcy 2011; Waldenbooks bankrupt earlier
- Amazon Prime (founded 2005): $99/year, unlimited free 2-day shipping; 20 million members; Prime members spend 2x as much as regular customers
- Amazon 2014: 232 million products, 244 million U.S. customers (defined as having purchased within past 12 months)
- Amazon costs: no sales tax collected (deprivation of billions in state/local revenue); excess retail mall space; future fewer construction, retail clerk, and manager jobs
- Gordon notes: "We return to this theme in chapter 17 as we explore the ever-growing set of forces that are slowing American economic growth to a crawl"

**Chapter 13 Conclusion**
- Mainframe to iPhone 6 (Sept 2014): complete transformation of how people communicate and obtain information
- Moore's Law died due to lack of demand — existing chips powerful enough for all required functions
- Mainframes first automated: telephone billing, phone switching (eliminated operators), ATM machines (replaced tellers), airline reservations
- 1970: handheld calculator eliminated slide rule and mechanical calculator overnight
- 1981: PC eliminated typewriter; electronic spreadsheet applied single formula to thousands of numbers
- Internet of 1995: "almost useless except for e-mail" — couldn't make hotel reservation, couldn't hear full song
- Key criticism of tech optimists: even rapid ICT progress can't overcome slowing progress in remaining 93% of economy

## Pages 541–560

### Chapter 13 Conclusion; Chapter 14: Health and Medicine

**Chapter 13 Conclusion (cont.)**
- WWW gave individuals new options: information became free, print encyclopedias obsolete, any information in seconds via search
- Long-distance phone calls eliminated letters; e-mail eliminated many phone calls; now Facebook/Twitter/Skype (video calls to soldiers in Afghanistan)
- Concerns: inequality in computer/internet access handicaps poor students competing against internet-literate classmates; Ronald Coase: "if you torture the data long enough, it will confess to anything"; Internet bullying; teenage boys losing concentration to YouTube, Facebook, games
- "A farmer with a smartphone today has better and faster access to information than a university professor two decades ago"

**Chapter 14: Health and Medicine — Overview**
- Chapter 7 covered 1870–1940; Chapter 14 covers 1940–2014
- Post-1940 life expectancy growth slowed to about half the pace of previous 70 years
- Shift from infant mortality gains to gains among older Americans
- Shift from acute infectious diseases to chronic disease management (heart disease, cancer)
- U.S. became least efficient major developed nation in healthcare: highest spending per capita, lower life expectancy than peers
- Post-1940 emphasis: technology-laden hospitals, specialized personnel → combined slowly improved health outcomes with perpetually rising costs

**Life Expectancy and Death Rates**
- Life expectancy gain 1880–1950: +25 years; gain 1950–2008: only +9 years
- Death rate per 100,000: fell 37.2% in first 40 years of 20th century; only 19.4% in following 60 years
- Post-1940 gains concentrated among elderly: overall life expectancy at birth +13% (1950–2008), but life expectancy at age 60 +33%
- By 1945: 2/3 of all deaths from chronic diseases (heart, cancer, stroke); only 25 years earlier 2/3 had been from infectious diseases

**Heart Disease**
- Biggest 20th-century killer: mortality rate actually ROSE between 1900 and 1940; peaked 1963 at 55% of all deaths
- Death rate from major CVD 1900: 345.2/100,000 (20% of all deaths); 1940: 485.7/100,000 (45% of all deaths)
- Decline after 1963: better blood pressure control, emergency rooms, coronary care units
- Heart disease still leading cause in 2010: 24.2% of deaths
- Recent slowdown: CHD mortality rate declined ~4%/year in late 1970s → 2.5% recently; men 35–54: fell 6.2%/year in 1980s → only 0.5%/year in 2000s
- Risk: "The United States might become the poster child not of the conquest of CHD but of its resurgence"

**Cancer**
- Cancer mortality: 64/100,000 (1900) → 120.3 (1940) → 200.5 (2000); 3x increase over century
- By 2010: cancer = 23.3% of all deaths, close to heart disease share
- Annual death toll rose 73% over past 30 years despite soaring funding — "one and a half times as fast as population growth"
- 5-year cancer survival rate: 50% (1971) → 63% (2004); despite $200 billion (inflation-adjusted) spent 1971–2004
- Problem in research: incentive to publish papers on narrow specific issues for funding; big picture falls by wayside
- "It's like a Greek tragedy. Everybody plays his individual part to perfection... and the total just doesn't work"
- Cancer chemotherapy: emerged from WWII (mustard gas → nitrogen mustards on cancer cells; 1948 Sidney Farber — "father of chemotherapy" — first complete leukemia remission in a child)
- CT imaging (1970s → widespread 1980s): eliminated need for exploratory surgery; mammogram (1973)
- CT scans: 75 million performed in 2009; 5–30% estimated unnecessary; CT scans in 2007 may produce 29,000 future cancers

**Penicillin and Antibiotics**
- Penicillin: discovered 1928 by Alexander Fleming (mold on dirty dish left out for weeks); WWII large-scale production subsidized by U.S. government
- Available in U.S. pharmacies summer 1945; price 6.5 cents/dose; U.S. penicillin market grew 7x between 1948–56 to 450,000 kg (3 grams per American)
- Cured: pneumonia ("Captain of the Men of Death"), rheumatic fever, syphilis (syphilis cases: 372/100,000 in 1938 → 154 in 1950 → 68 in 1960)
- Rheumatic fever death rate fell 90% between 1940–60; children's pneumonia deaths fell to 1/4 of 1939 level by 1954
- FDA approved 50% more new drugs 1940–60 than in the next 51 years combined
- Streptomycin eliminated TB as major U.S. disease; TB incidence fell 2/3 between 1944–60; by 2001: <6/100,000 Americans had TB
- "The middle of the twentieth century [was] the end of one of the most important social revolutions in history — the virtual elimination of infectious disease as a significant factor in social life" (Robert Bud)

**Polio Vaccine**
- Polio: not a major killer but deeply feared as "leading crippler of children" — heightened because FDR had it
- March of Dimes: more public support than any other health campaign
- Salk vaccine (1955): largest clinical trial in history — 400,000+ children immunized; Sabin vaccine (1960, oral) became more prevalent
- By late 1960s: polio virus entirely eliminated in United States

**AIDS/HIV**
- HIV identified 1981 as terrifying mystery; AZT approved 1987 (first anti-HIV drug) — only somewhat effective, negative side effects
- By 1995: 500,000+ AIDS cases reported, 300,000+ Americans dead; leading cause of death ages 25–44
- ART (antiretroviral therapy): turned HIV from death sentence to chronic manageable disease; 1.2 million Americans currently living with HIV with "almost normal lifespan"

**Smoking**
- Cigarettes peaked 1963 at 4,300/person/year; declined to 1,230 by 2011
- Smoker prevalence: fell 17 points (42.4% → 25.5%) in 25 years after 1965; then only 5 points (to 20.6%) in next 19 years
- Smoking still costs $200 billion/year in healthcare + lost productivity
- Hardest to eliminate smoking among poorest: adult rate fell 27% since 1997 overall, but only 15% for poor; important driver of slower life expectancy growth at bottom of income distribution

**Mental Health**
- WWII: 850,000 soldiers treated for "psychoneurotic" issues; psychiatric officers multiplied by 100
- Pre-WWII: psychiatry institutionally marginal, focused on the "insane"; after: moved into mainstream, focused on mental health of general population
- Current serious mental illness: >$190 billion/year in lost earnings

**Air Pollution**
- 1963 Clean Air Act: first law to control (not just study) air pollution; 1970 amendments set specific air quality standards
- LA ozone levels 60% lower today than mid-1970s
- Reduced smog 1980–2000 accounted for ~15% of 2.7-year life expectancy gain over that period

**Accidents and Violence**
- Accidents (2011): 126,000 deaths, 40.6/100,000 — fifth most prevalent cause of death
- Non-automobile accident rate: 94/100,000 (1906) → 46 (1940) → minimum 18 (1980) → back up to 30 (2011)
- Homicide rate: peaked 8–10/100,000 both in 1921–36 AND 1970–96
- 1970s–80s crime surge: mugger jokes became standard comedy; "Central Park as well-known death trap"; NY apartments had multiple latches and "police locks"; Boston's "Combat Zone"
- Rape rate: began declining late 1970s (partly from feminist movement + Susan Brownmiller's 1975 "Against Our Will"); by 2009 rate = 1/5 of its 1973 level

## Pages 561–580

### Chapter 14 (continued): Medical Profession, Healthcare Costs, and Medical System

**Violence (cont.)**
- Homicide rate: 10.5/100,000 (1991) → 5.5 by 2000; theories for decline: better law enforcement, cultural "civilizing," Roe v. Wade (1973) reducing unwanted births

**Changes in the Medical Profession**
- Pre-1938: pharmacy was "wild West" of unregulated drugs; 1938 FDA legislation required prescriptions for some drugs
- Prescription drug share of pharmacy sales: 12% (1940) → 40% (1965); drug firms directed 60% of advertising to physicians by 1961
- Specialist share of doctors: 24% (1940) → 69% (1966); doctors per 10,000 population: 13 (1950s) → 31 (2009)
- 1972: first legal requirement for informed consent (federal appeals court, DC); 1973 American Hospital Association Patients' Bill of Rights
- Today: fewer than 30% of U.S. doctors are generalists; most advanced countries have at least 50% generalists — "silent crisis undermining US health care"

**Medical Technology: Promises and Limits**
- MRI: first introduced 1977; radiation-free alternative/complement to CT scan; use of MRI and CT both grew 8%+/year since mid-1990s; $100+ billion/year spent on medical imaging total
- Human genome project (started 1995): evidentiary framework for FDA approval still undeveloped; "remains to be seen whether genomic medicine will actually improve health"
- Stem cell therapy: practiced since late 1980s for bone marrow transplants, but practical application barely extended beyond that; "stem cell research" cited 11x more often than "stem cell therapy" in 2008 books
- Drug costs: NMEs (new molecular entities) produced at steady pace but R&D cost per NME rising 13.4%/year since 1950s; Pfizer spent $7 billion on R&D in 2007 but produced few innovative drugs
- Regulatory barriers: "intolerance for even a minimum of casualties... has now reached a level that effectively constrains any further attempts to seriously innovate"
- Incentive problem: "unraveling of molecular pathways, not their use in clinical interventions, is the way to get scientific recognition, publications and promotion... to publish a paper describing merely a new cure for cancer has much less priority than hard core science"

**Hospitals: "Gleaming Palaces of Science and Waste"**
- Hill-Burton Act (1946): funded 4,678 hospital projects over 20 years; guideline of 4.5 hospital beds per 1,000 population; hospital admissions +26% in 6 years after 1946
- By 1960: virtually every short-stay hospital had diagnostic X-rays, clinical labs, postoperative recovery rooms
- ICUs: 1/7 of not-for-profit hospitals had them in 1961 → more than 1/2 by 1969
- "Medical arms race": no supervisory body prevents duplicate hospitals or equipment in adjacent locations; happens most in affluent insured suburbs
- Indiana 1978: 1 CT scanner per 100,000 people vs. 1 per 1 million in Canada, 1 per 2 million in Britain — no apparent advantage in outcomes
- Paul Starr's epigraph: "gleaming palaces of modern science... stood next to neighborhoods that had been medically abandoned, that had no doctors for everyday needs"
- University of Chicago Medical Center: closed trauma center 1988 to cut costs; closest trauma ward became 10+ miles away from south side (where much of city's gun violence occurs); 18-year-old Damian Turner shot nearby in 2010, had to be taken 8+ miles to another hospital, died
- For-profit hospitals (1981): daily costs 23% higher than not-for-profit counterparts despite expectation of greater efficiency

**Medicare/Medicaid and Insurance System**
- Blue Cross (hospital) and Blue Shield (physician payments) created early 1930s; WWII frozen wages → employers offered health benefits → employer-based insurance became standard
- Health insurance enrollment: 12 million (1940) → widespread after WWII
- Employment-based system was regressive: uninsured faced personal bankruptcy from major illnesses
- Medicare and Medicaid (mid-1960s): poor saw doctors 20% less than nonpoor (1964) → reversed entirely by 1975; hospital inpatients 65+ rose from 16% to 30% (1965–85)
- Third-party system fueled cost spiral: "hospitals could pass costs to insurers, who could pass them to subscribers... an expansionary spiral"
- Healthcare expenditures as % of GNP: 4.5% (1950) → 9.4% (1980) → 17.7% (2010)

**Hospital Cost Containment Failures**
- 1980s: Medicare introduced 467 Diagnosis-Related Groups (DRGs) with standardized reimbursements; hospitals cut quality to maximize profit margin
- Consequences: patients discharged too early, denied admission with multiple serious conditions
- Average hospital stay: 7.3 days (1980) → 4.9 days (2000); elderly: 12.6 days (1970) → 6 days (2000)
- Broken hip patients: 20 days (1981) → 7 days (1998); patients "in relatively worse health as they were discharged"

**HMOs and Managed Care**
- HMO concept: Paul Elwood admired Kaiser Permanente and Mayo Clinic fixed-fee group practices; coined "health maintenance organizations" 1973; HMO Act of 1973
- But Nixon's version expanded beyond Elwood's ideal; by 1997, two-thirds of HMO business was for-profit commercial insurance
- For-profit HMOs: imposed criteria on physicians remotely, required prior approval for referrals and tests; physician income based on cutting costs, not health outcomes
- Response: PPOs (preferred provider organizations) = "half-hearted HMOs"; 56% of insured employees in PPOs by 2010; traditional fee-for-service fell from 73% (1988) to mere 1% (2010)
- Healthcare share of GDP stabilized briefly 1993–2000 (13.5% → 13.8%); $300 billion lower than projected; then resumed rise to 17.7% by 2010

**Quality of Life Gains (Beyond Life Expectancy)**
- Hip/knee replacement surgery: 332,000 hip replacements and 719,000 knee replacements (2014); each hip replacement provides ~0.8 extra QALYs over 5 years
- Birth control pill: FDA approval 1960; 6.5 million women using by 1965; derived from Mexican yam; called "after penicillin the most important pharmaceutical development of the 20th century"
- Pill ended baby boom (1947–64); enabled women to enter labor force; most rapid increase in female labor-force participation 1965–85
- Viagra (sildenafil): synthesized 1989 by Pfizer employees; on market late 1990s; contributes to QALYs for aging population
- Fluoridation: Grand Rapids MI first city (January 1945); became U.S. Public Health Service policy 1951; now reaches 64% of population; reduces tooth decay by 56% (Irish Republic comparison study)
- Air conditioning and heat mortality: mortality impact of days >80°F has declined 70% since 1960; entire decline attributable to residential A/C diffusion

**Healthcare Inequality**
- Black-white life expectancy gap: ~15 years (1900) → 7.6 years (1970) → 3.5 years (2011) — narrowing but persistent
- Black infant mortality rate: 2x white rate in 2011
- Cancer 5-year survival: 68.6% (white) vs. 59.4% (black) 2001–2007
- White women without high school diploma lost 5 years of life expectancy between 1990–2008 — "a measure of decline last seen among Russians after the fall of the Soviet Union"
- Female mortality rose in >40% of U.S. counties since early 1990s
- U.S. vs. Canada: 55% higher healthcare spending, 2.5 years shorter life expectancy; U.S. vs. Italy/UK: 2x+ healthcare spending, ~4 years shorter life expectancy
- U.S. excess spending breakdown (vs. Canada): 39% administrative, 31% higher physician incomes, 14% additional procedures, 16% unallocated

## Pages 581–600

### Chapter 14 Conclusion; Chapter 15: Work, Youth, Retirement

**Chapter 14 Conclusion**
- Most important post-1940 innovations occurred early: 1940–late 1970s; antibiotics eradicated infectious diseases; CVD and cancer main treatments developed by 1970s
- War on cancer was NOT successful — few breakthroughs since 1970s imaging and chemotherapy
- After 1970: high-tech expensive hospitals; "technological emporiums" AND "cold mechanical treatment centers"; simple preventive measures underemphasized
- New drug development slowed; genome and stem cells "thus far slow to produce effective drugs and therapies"; recent breakthroughs largely disease management, not cures
- Healthcare share of GDP: only 4% between 1930–60; reached 18% by 2013; sixth of population still lacked insurance; U.S. life expectancy 2–4 years shorter than other developed countries
- Obamacare (2010): 142 different plan options in Illinois alone; narrow provider networks with high doctor turnover; doctors "come in and out of the network all the time, like players switching teams in the NBA"; avoided single-payer model due to private insurance lobbying; helped bridge coverage gap with subsidies; at least temporarily appeared to stop GDP share creep by 2013

**Chapter 15 Overview: Work, Youth, Retirement**
- Working conditions improved most dramatically 1870–1940; since 1940, improvements present but slower
- Manufacturing jobs peaked at ~30% of labor force in 1953 → fell to 10% by 2015; well-paying blue-collar union jobs disappeared
- $20/hour wage (introduced at scale mid-20th century): "allowed masses of Americans with no more than high school education to rise to the middle class... on its way to extinction" (Uchitelle)
- Social Security (1935): ended concept of "working until you dropped" — enabled retirement; retirement culture spawned golf courses, retirement homes, Sun City AZ, mass migration to Sun Belt

**Shift From Farm/Factory to Office**
- Agriculture employment: 40% (1900) → 20% (1940) → 10% (1953) → 5% (1967) → 2% (2000–2013)
- Coal mining fatality rate: 329/100,000 miners (1911–15) → 25 (1996–97)
- Air conditioning raised government typist productivity 25% in 1950s; rated chief boost to worker productivity by 90% of American firms in 1957 survey
- Without A/C: "seasonal cycles determined by weather... workers left early and businesses shut their doors. Cities emptied in summers"
- Air conditioning may help explain why TFP growth was higher before 1970 than after — most indoor jobs benefited from A/C by 1970

**The Great Compression (1945–1975)**
- Claudia Goldin and Robert Margo: "Great Compression" of U.S. socioeconomic classes 1945–1975
- Blue-collar union worker could live next door to accountant or teacher; "postwar America had no working class and no working-class politics — it had a middle-class politics for an expanding middle class"
- Werner Sombart (1906): "Socialism in America foundered upon roast beef and apple pie" — expanding postwar middle class barely proved him wrong
- Between 1970–1998: average income in top 0.01% jumped from 50 to 250 times the economy-wide average — Great Compression replaced by "Great Divergence"

**The Feminine Revolution**
- WWII: 5.2 million women entered labor force; "Rosie the Riveter" symbol of female patriotism
- Personal savings peaked 1943–44 at 27% of household disposable income (vs. normal 5–10%)
- Baby boom fertility rate: 2.4 (1945) → 3.3 (1947) → 3.8 (1956) → 2.4 (1970)
- 1950s homemakers: average 56 hours/week in home production; each child under 1 year added 17 hours/week; youngest child 1–5 added 7 hours/week
- 1960: 60% of women who entered college quit before graduation — often to "earn their Ph.T." (Put Hubby Through)
- Cultural expectation: Seventeen magazine: "being a woman is your career... there is no office, lab, or stage that offers so many creative avenues as that everyday place, the home"
- Sandra Day O'Connor: graduated Stanford Law, turned down by 40 law firms, initially worked as legal secretary
- Medical school dean 1961: "Hell yes, we have a quota. Yes, it's a small one. We do keep women out when we can. We don't want them here"
- 1960: women = 6% of doctors, 3% of lawyers, <1% of engineers; 1.4% of top civil service pay grades (despite >50% of federal employees being women)
- Prime-age female LFPR: 34.9% (1948) → 44.5% (1964) → 69.6% (1985) → peak 76.8% (1999) → 73.9% (2014)
- Prime-age male LFPR: 96.8% (1964) → 91.7% (1999) → 88.2% (2014) — slowly declining as women rose; gap barely narrowed after 1999
- Female wages as % of male wages: 58.8% (1975) → 71.6% (1990) → 77.4% (2010) annual earnings; 81% for weekly earnings
- Claudia Goldin's "Quiet Revolution" (post-1970): women invested in education, planned careers rather than jobs
- 1960: 94% of doctors, 96% of lawyers, 86% of managers were white men; by 2008: 63%, 61%, 57% respectively
- Recent years: women under 30 earn more than male counterparts on average (except in 3 largest cities); 3 men lost jobs per woman during recent recession
- Men: 87% of manufacturing, 71% of construction — declining industries; women dominating growing white-collar professions

**Education Trends**
- High school completion rate: 10% (1900) → 75% (1970) → little further progress since 1970
- GI Bill: paid college expenses for millions of returning veterans → U.S. led world in college completion percentage
- College completion rank: fell from 1st in world to no better than 15th in past two decades
- 40% of recent college graduates unable to find jobs requiring college education
- College price increase (inflation-adjusted): factor of 10 since the 1950s; student debt total: $1.2 trillion

## Pages 601–620

### Chapter 15 (continued) and Entr'acte: Transition to Part III

**Gender Wage Gap Analysis (Goldin)**
- Residual wage gap (explained by identifiable characteristics like education) has shrunk as men and women converged in human capital; BUT remaining unexplained "residual" gap still large
- Occupational choices explain only ~1/3 of remaining residual wage gap; ~2/3 is within-occupation differences
- Women's earnings fall further behind as they age: 25–30 age group: 10% gap; 45–50 age group: 35% gap
- Key insight: occupations where ONE specific person must always be available (trial lawyers, M&A bankers, surgeons, Secretary of State) penalize time flexibility; pharmacists, physicians in group practices do NOT
- Trend: large chain drugstores and group medical practices make individuals more substitutable → reducing the within-occupation gender penalty

**College Education**
- College completion (ages 25–29): 5% (1940) → 10% (1966) → 20% (1990) → 32% (2013)
- Male–female enrollment: peaked at 72% male in 1949–50 (GI Bill peak); fell below 50% male in 1978; by 2013: 58% female / 42% male
- Educational attainment stagnation: born 1925 = 10.9 years avg; born 1950 = 13.2 years; born 1975 = 13.9 years — barely moved in second 25-year cohort
- 2002 median annual earnings: HS dropout $23K, HS grad $30K, bachelor's $47K, master's+ $60K — NO real growth for ANY group over 17 years of data
- College graduate unemployment consistently ~half the rate of high school graduates since 1992
- Warning: 40% of recent college graduates can't find jobs requiring college education; some driving taxis or working at Starbucks; forced to move back with parents; delaying marriage/household formation

**Pension/Retirement**
- Pre-1935: workers "worked until they dropped"; private pension coverage only 10% of workforce by 1930; Great Depression eliminated most private pensions
- Social Security (1935): poverty rate among elderly fell from 35% (1959) to 10% (2003)
- Private pension coverage: 7% of labor force (1940) → 28% (1960) → 45% (1970); private plans held 7% of U.S. financial assets (1970) vs. 2% in 1950
- ERISA (1974): required vesting of pension benefits; created Pension Benefit Guaranty Corporation (paid benefits to 1.3 million workers from 4,140 terminated plans by 2010)
- Sun City, Arizona: Del Webb launched 1960; 26,000 units in Maricopa County; age-restricted communities grew to 771 by 2013
- Retirement culture: more TV (4.2 hours/day retirees vs. 2.75 total population); more relaxing, thinking, reading
- GI generation retirees: ended arduous physical labor; baby boomers: many choosing to keep working past 65
- Defined-benefit pension plans: 30% of workers (1983) → 15% (2013); about 33% of retirees 65+ live ONLY on Social Security
- 2008–09 crisis: many 401(k) holders "bought high and sold low" converting stocks to cash at market bottom
- 2030 projection: 2 workers per retiree (vs. 5 workers per retiree in 1960); "Demography is destiny"
- 49% of middle-class workers projected to be poor or near-poor during retirement
- Age discrimination study: 4,000 résumés sent to firms with varying stated ages; younger workers (35) were 40% more likely to get a callback than workers over 50

**Sources of Slowing Growth (Chapter 15 conclusion)**
- Women's shift from home to market work (1960–90) may have accounted for 15–20% of U.S. economic growth; this tailwind is now over — female LFPR declining since 2000
- Wage gaps between white men and black men at steady plateau since 1990 — another source of allocation improvement that's exhausted
- High school completion plateaued at ~75% in 1970; college attainment growing slowly; college debt burden may soon stop or reverse college degree growth

**Entr'acte: Understanding Slower Growth**
- Part I (chapters 2–8): 1870–1940 special century
- Part II (chapters 10–15): 1940–2014 mixed record
- 1970 = distinct break point between faster and slower growth
- Growth in output per person = labor productivity growth + hours worked per person
- After late 1960s: labor productivity growth slowed; but OUTPUT PER PERSON did not similarly slow until after 2000 — because women entering labor force raised hours worked per person
- Since 2000: sharp decline in BOTH labor productivity growth AND hours worked per person — "the book's title, The Rise and Fall of American Growth, has become a statement of fact"

**Sector-by-Sector Growth Record since 1970**
- FASTER after 1970: entertainment/communication (Ch. 12) and digital equipment (Ch. 13); no post-1970 slowdown; smartphones/streaming/social media constitute acceleration
- ICT peak: pronounced productivity peak 1996–2004 from web/search/e-commerce/ICT investment; Moore's Law slowing since 2005
- SLOWER/MINOR after 1940: food (processed food and refrigeration already transformed pre-1940); clothing (already transformed pre-1940 from make-at-home to buy; postwar just style shifts and cheaper imports); housing (by 1940 already fully networked in urban America; 1940–70 was just catching up for farms/small towns)
- Transportation: little improvement in motor vehicle travel after 1970; interstate highway system largely complete by 1970; airline quality actually DECLINED after 1970 (seating, meals, security); fatality rates improved for both
- Medicine: three stages — (1) infant mortality largely conquered by 1950; (2) antibiotics and CVD/cancer treatment mostly complete by 1970; (3) since 1970: incremental improvements, smoking reduction, hip/knee replacements — but slower than prior era
- Work conditions: nothing after 1940 compared to pre-1940 gains (shorter hours, less drudgery, networked house, end of child labor, Social Security, Civil Rights/Voting Rights Acts)

## Pages 621–640

### Entr'acte (continued) and Chapter 16: The Great Leap Forward

**Entr'acte: Output Mismeasurement and Sources of Growth**
- Even in post-1940 era, real GDP understated true growth via: omitted value of A/C diffusion, unmeasured quality improvements in TV sets, improvements in life expectancy not captured, civil rights and women's labor force entry
- BUT: understatement was LESS after 1970 than before — automobile quality and housing size captured more accurately; computer prices captured by hedonic index after 1986; nature of change itself became less revolutionary
- Key argument: GDP understatement of smartphone is real but people forget GDP has understated everything since the beginning — and pre-1970 innovations (indoor plumbing, infant mortality reduction, refrigeration) were far more important than multifunction smartphone
- "Those who complain that GDP doesn't give credit to the smartphone are correct as far as they go, but they often fail to realize that GDP has understated progress since the beginning of recorded economic history and for innovative changes far more important than the multifunction smartphone"

**Four Headwinds (Preview — detailed in Ch. 18)**
1. INEQUALITY: late 1970s onward — rising top 1% income share; superstar effect; winner-take-all; CEO pay surges; declining unions, declining real minimum wage; automation and globalization shrinking good middle-income jobs
2. EDUCATION: high school completion plateaued at 75–80% since 1970; college completion rising slowly; 40% of graduates can't find jobs requiring college education; student debt burden
3. DEMOGRAPHIC: hours per person rising (1960s–2000) as women entered labor force; now DECLINING since 2000 (prime-age male AND female LFPR declining); baby boomer retirement accelerating decline after 2008
4. FISCAL: inevitable future increase in federal debt/GDP ratio; future benefit cuts + tax increases will reduce disposable income growth

**Chapter 16: The Great Leap Forward (1920s–1950s)**
- "One of the greatest achievements in all of economic history"
- Had 1870–1928 growth rate continued, by 1950 output per hour would have been 52% higher than 1928; ACTUAL 1928–50 increase: 99% — nearly doubled the expected pace
- Great Leap "puzzle": Great Inventions had already reached most urban households by 1928 — electricity, gas, telephone, running water, sewers all connected; 93% of Iowa farmers owned a motor vehicle by 1926 (from 0% in 1900)

**The Quantitative Evidence**
- 1870–1928 trend: output per hour and output per person both grew at 1.9%/year
- Post-1928 divergence: productivity (output per hour) barely fell during Great Depression but soared to 32% above trend by 1957 and 44% above trend in 1972
- Output per person: collapsed during Depression, soared during WWII, then settled 10–35% above trend in postwar decades
- Hours per person: declined markedly (effect of unions achieving 8-hour day + baby boom mothers staying home with children)
- Capital productivity (output/capital ratio): nearly doubled between 1920s and 1950s (176% of 1928 value by 1950 in official data; ~141% after adjustment for measurement issues)
- After adjustment, about HALF of jump in output-capital ratio is from measurement issues; remaining half is real productivity gain

**Growth Accounting Framework**
- Growth accounting (pioneered by Robert Solow 1950s; Denison, Griliches, Jorgenson 1960s) decomposes labor productivity growth into:
  1. Labor quality (educational attainment)
  2. Capital quantity per unit of labor
  3. Capital quality
  4. TFP (total factor productivity) — "the measure of our ignorance" — everything else including innovation, tinkering, efficiency improvements, shift from farm to city
- Key finding: educational attainment rose at STEADY pace before and after 1928 — so it CANNOT explain the Great Leap (it was a constant contributor, not an accelerating one)

**New Deal and Labor Unions Boosted Productivity**
- National Industrial Recovery Act (1933–35) and National Labor Relations Act (Wagner Act, 1935): made union organizing much easier; pushed up real wages
- Fair Labor Standards Act (1938): codified 40-hour week with mandatory 1.5x overtime for hours beyond 40
- Real wage vs. trend: real wage was 14% above trend by 1941 (slightly ahead of productivity's 11%)
- Mechanism: higher wages → firms economized on labor → substituted capital for labor → higher productivity per worker
- Edward Denison: shorter work hours reduced fatigue → directly improved worker efficiency; establishments reorganized to do same work in 8 hours as formerly in 10
- High school graduation 1900–1970: 6% → 80%; by 1940 half of youth had completed high school; more capable workforce for WWII production challenges

**GI Bill and Educational Attainment**
- GI Bill (1944): paid ALL college expenses for WWII veterans; 16.1 million served (12% of 1940 population); swamped colleges 1946–49
- Also: funding to complete high school; low-interest home purchase loans; unemployment compensation for first year after service
- Elementary school-only workers: 75% (1915) → 30% (1960) → 3% (2005)
- College/post-graduate workers: 4% (1915) → 48% (2005)

**WWII as Economic Miracle**
- The most novel thesis: WWII itself was perhaps the most important contributor to the Great Leap
- Military spending in 1944: 80% of the entire economy's 1939 size; real GDP in 1944 was almost double 1939
- War created massive household savings (rationing + production prohibitions = nothing to buy on); personal savings rate peaked 1943–44 at 27% (vs. normal 5–10%)
- "Pent-up demand": after 1945, households spent war savings on consumer goods → the classic pent-up demand release
- Government paid for new factories and equipment, operated by private firms → massive expansion of capital stock WWII not paid for by private savings but by government deficit
- Supply channels: infrastructure investments (Golden Gate Bridge, Bay Bridge, TVA, Hoover Dam); "learning by doing" under war production constraints; firms devised new techniques when constrained by limited capital/labor

## Pages 661–680

**Chapter 16 Conclusion: The Great Leap Forward — Final Explanations**
- Federal government purchased productive equipment 1941–45 equal to roughly 50% of entire pre-war privately owned equipment stock — and it was ALL more modern than existing capital
- Electricity expansion: for every 100 units added 1902–29, another 230 units were added 1929–1950 — Paul David's dynamo story is really about the 1929–1950 period, not just the 1920s
- Innovation did NOT slow during the Depression: Alexopoulos/Cohen technical books data and Kleinknecht's inventions-by-decade both show dominance of 1920–1950 period
- Great Depression trauma → accelerated patent/innovation activity in late 1930s; auto quality, radio, film, plastics all advanced rapidly
- Two overriding conclusions: (1) WWII saved U.S. from secular stagnation — hypothetical no-war scenario after 1939 looks "dismal at best"; (2) Great Inventions of late 19th century continued to transform production in 1930s and 1940s, not just 1920s
- Alex Field's claim that 1930s were the "most progressive decade" validated; this book's finding of even faster 1941–50 growth does not diminish Field's contribution

**Chapter 17 Introduction: Can the Future Match the Great Inventions?**
- Opening epigraph: Peter Thiel — "We wanted flying cars, instead we got 140 characters."
- IR #2 (1870–1940, benefits extending to 1970): unprecedented tidal wave of inventions; many benefits unmeasured by GDP (electric light vs. oil lamps, piped water, conquest of infant mortality)
- IR #3 (computers/digitalization): slower measured productivity since 1970 is key evidence IR #3 < IR #2 in impact; unmeasured improvements from IR #3 also less profound
- IR #3 narrowly focused: entertainment, ICT — IR #2 changed food, clothing, appliances, housing, transportation, health, working conditions
- U-shaped innovation history: individual inventors dominated late 19th century → corporate R&D labs dominated 20th century → individual entrepreneurs returned post-1975 (Gates, Jobs, Bezos, Zuckerberg)
- TFP chronology: 1994–2004 was the only meaningful revival post-1970; 1970–94 = 0.57%/yr; 1994–2004 = 1.03%/yr; 2004–14 = 0.40%/yr — all far below 1.89%/yr of 1920–70
- Key questions: Why was IR #3's TFP effect limited to just 1994–2004? Why so slow 2004–14? What does this imply for next 25 years?

**The U-Shaped History of Innovation**
- Late 19th century: individual entrepreneurs — Edison, Wright Brothers, Bell, Benz (German), Morse (telegraph 1844), McCormick (reaper 1834)
- Patents per million population: 18 (1790–1830) → 89 (1830–1870) → 344 (1870–1940) → 275 (1940–1985) → 485 (1985–2012)
- Share of patents to individuals: 95% (1880) → 73% (1920) → 42% (1940) → 21% (1970) → 15% (2000)
- By 2000: of the 85% not to individuals, split nearly evenly between U.S. firms (44%) and foreign firms (41%)
- Corporate lab era: GM research labs, Bell Labs (transistor invented by William Shockley team, late 1947), IBM corporate R&D (mainframes 1950–80), RCA (TV), GE/Whirlpool (appliances)
- IBM PC decision (1981): IBM farmed out OS software ownership to Paul Allen and Bill Gates (Harvard dropout, founded Microsoft 1975) — pivotal right-turn back to individuals
- Individual entrepreneurs of IR #3: Gates/Allen (Microsoft), Steve Jobs (Apple), Jeff Bezos (Amazon), Sergei Brin and Larry Page (Google), Mark Zuckerberg (Facebook)
- Patent share of individuals stays flat at 15% — because individuals now quickly form corporations; Gates' patents credited to Microsoft, not to Gates personally
- U.S. patent system deliberately democratic: only 5% of British fee; detailed specs made public immediately; licensing much more extensive than Europe
- Result: many U.S. inventors had only elementary/secondary education — could patent without large investment, attract capital after grant
- Antonio Meucci: developed telephone before Bell but couldn't afford Italian patent fees — contrast shows U.S. system democratized invention
- February 14, 1876: both Elisha Gray and Alexander Graham Bell arrived at patent office to register telephone technologies — Bell arrived hours earlier, became rich and famous; Gray forgotten
- Diminishing returns pattern: patent counts for autos, airplanes, radio all show initial explosion then plateau or decline — autos absolute decline after 1925
- Evsey Domar (1961): without technical change, capital accumulation = "piling wooden plows on top of existing wooden plows"
- Solow's result: only 13% of output per worker growth 1910–1950 came from capital per worker increase — "took the capital out of capitalism"

**TFP Record Since 1970**
- TFP annual growth: 1890–1920 ~0.6%; 1920–1970 = 1.89%; 1970–94 = 0.57%; 1994–2004 = 1.03%; 2004–2014 = 0.40%
- IR #2 TFP surge lasted 50 years; IR #3 revival lasted only 10 years and smaller in magnitude
- Paul David's dynamo lag: IR #2 inventions mainly 1870–1900 but TFP surge came 1920–1970 — 40-year implementation lag; same story for automobiles (Benz 1879 → Ford assembly line 1913)
- IR #3 same delay: mainframes transformed business from 1960s, PCs from 1980s, but main TFP impact not until 1994–2004 (Internet, web browsers, search, e-commerce)

**Was IR #3 Almost Over by 2004?**
- Solow quip: "You can see the computer age everywhere but in the productivity statistics" — described the 1970–94 puzzle
- Gordon's resolution: computers are NOT everywhere — "We don't eat computers or wear them or drive to work in them or let them cut our hair"
- ICT barely touched: food, clothing, motor vehicles, furniture, appliances, rent, health care, education, personal care — two-thirds of consumption is services, mostly untouched by ICT
- "A pedicure is a pedicure regardless of whether the customer is reading a Kindle or surfing the web on a smartphone"
- 1994–2004 revival: marriage of computers and communication — Internet, web browsers, e-mail all became universal within brief interval 1993–1998
- Amazon (1994), Google (1998), Wikipedia (2001), iTunes (2001), Facebook (2004) — all now more than a decade old by the time of writing
- Office transformation 1970–2005: electric typewriters → PCs → web-linked PCs → flat screens and broadband → by 2005 the modern office was essentially complete
- Catalog revolution 1980s–1990s: library card catalogs → electronic; auto dealer parts → electronic — all happened 15–25 years ago; "one-time-only jump in the level of productivity"
- Post-2005 stasis: "Throughout the world, the equipment used in office work and the productivity of office employees closely resembles that of a decade ago"
- Smartphones in office: 90% of workers visit recreational websites during workday; 70% tracked visiting retail sites — smartphones used for personal activities, dragging down productivity
- Small continued improvements: service technicians with tablets, airline pilots with tablets, nuclear plant crews trading binders for iPads — marginal gains only

## Pages 681–700

**IR #3 Achievements: Retailing, Finance, Banking**
- Retail productivity revolution largely complete: Walmart and big-box stores transformed supply chains, wholesale distribution, inventory management, pricing — "that productivity-enhancing shift away from traditional small-scale retailing is largely over"
- E-commerce 2000–2014 grew 11-fold nominally BUT still only 6.4% of all retail sales in 2014 — too small to have major economy-wide impact
- ATMs and bank branches: ATMs reduced employees per branch from ~20 (1988) to ~13 (2004) → banks INCREASED branches by 43% over same period → total bank tellers only fell from 484,000 (1985) to 361,000 (recent) — robots often complement rather than replace
- James Bessen: bookkeeping software invention did NOT prevent number of accounting clerks from growing 1999–2009 — another example of complementarity
- NYSE daily shares traded: 3.5 million (1960) → 1.7 billion (2005) → declined to 1.2 billion (2015) — finance/banking innovation peaked in 1990s, now plateaued
- Home appliances: all major ones (washer, dryer, refrigerator, range, dishwasher, garbage disposer) invented before WWII, reached most households by early 1970s — home stable for nearly a HALF CENTURY before writing
- Consumer electronics: video cassette recorder (CES 1970), compact disc (CES 1981), HDTV (CES 1998), Xbox (CES 2001) — "this year's crop of products seemed a bit underwhelming by comparison"
- Smartphones/tablets: "now that smartphones and tablets have saturated their potential market, further advances in consumer electronics have become harder to achieve"

**Decline in Business Dynamism**
- Young firms (≤5 years old) as share of all firms: 14.6% (1978) → 8.3% (2011) — nearly halved, and this decline started BEFORE the 2008–09 financial crisis
- Young firms' share of total employment: 19.2% (1982) → 10.7% (2011) — pervasive across retailing, services, and post-2000 high-tech
- People under 30 owning stakes in private companies: 10.6% (1989) → 3.6% (2014) — sharp decline in entrepreneurship
- Job reallocation rates fell more than a quarter after 1990; worker reallocation rates fell more than a quarter after 2000
- "Declining dynamism of American society" — slower startups, job creation, job destruction, internal migration all moving in same direction

**Objective Measures of Slowdown (vs. 1994–2004 Uniqueness)**
- Manufacturing capacity growth: 2–3%/yr (1972–94) → surge to almost 7%/yr (late 1990s) → back down to NEGATIVE growth in 2012
- Stripping out ICT production: TFP in manufacturing was only 0.3%/yr between 1987–2011 (Baily and Bosworth); Acemoglu et al. found no tendency for labor productivity to grow faster in "ICT-intensive" industries outside ICT production itself
- Net investment ratio: 3.2% long-run average; exceeded that average for only four years (1999–2002); fell to 1.0% in 2013 — less than a THIRD of historical average
- ICT equipment deflator (rate of price decline): peaked at –14%/yr in 1999; steadily decreased to barely –1%/yr by 2010–14
- ICT contribution to labor productivity: 0.52 percentage points/yr (1995–2004) → 0.19 points/yr (2004–2013)
- Moore's Law: doubled transistors on track for ~2 years between 1975–1990; plunged to 14 months in 2000 (dot-com peak); then SOARED to 8 years in 2009, came back to 4 years in 2014 — "Moore's Law has gone off the rails" since 2006
- Kenneth Flamm: "clock speed" (measure of computer performance) has been on a PLATEAU of no change since 2003
- Four factors unique to late 1990s: surge in manufacturing capacity, rise in net investment ratio, trough in computer price decline, acceleration of Moore's Law — "all create a strong case that the dot-com era was unique"

**Can Future Innovation Be Predicted?**
- Joel Mokyr: "History is always a bad guide to the future and economic historians should avoid making predictions" — pessimists condemned for lack of imagination
- Gordon's counter: future innovation IS partially forecastable — historical precedents exist
- Jules Verne, 1863 Paris in the Twentieth Century: predicted rapid transit on overhead viaducts, gas combustion motor cars, and street lights connected by underground wires — written BEFORE Edison or Benz
- Ladies Home Journal, December 1900: accurate forecasts included air conditioning from spigots, ready-cooked meal establishments, liquid-air refrigerators, photographs telegraphed within an hour (news photography), automobiles cheaper than horses, remote video communication ("lips of a remote actor heard when seen to move")
- 1939–40 New York World's Fair: accurately forecast superhighways, air-conditioned homes, television following radio model — easy to extrapolate from then-current trends
- Missing at 1939–40 Fair: any vision of the computer revolution (IR #3)
- Norbert Wiener (1949 essay rejected by NYT): predicted machines would "reduce the economic value of the routine factory employee to a point at which he is not worth hiring at any price" and warned of AI safety ("every degree of independence we give the machine is a degree of possible defiance of our wishes")
- Unfulfilled predictions: Dick Tracy wrist radio (finally arrived as Apple Watch, 70 years later); Jetsons' vertical commuting car/plane never happened; high-fuel-cost killed helicopter short-haul aviation companies

**Future Innovations: Assessment of Techno-Optimist Claims**
- Brynjolfsson and McAfee: "we're at an inflection point" — claim Big Blue chess and Watson on Jeopardy presage computers outsmarting humans in all work
- Gordon's rebuttal: Brynjolfsson/McAfee ignore that Moore's Law has fallen behind predicted pace after 2005; exponential performance increases continuing but at SLOWER rate, not faster
- Medical/pharmaceutical: most important life expectancy advances came in FIRST half of 20th century (infant mortality, germ theory, sanitation); medical tech continuing at "slow and measured pace"; pharmaceutical research "reached a brick wall" — declining major drugs approved per two-year period; Alzheimer's care a rising burden
- Small robots: GM introduced industrial robots 1961; by 1990s welding auto parts and replacing workers in paint shops; Baxter robot in 2012 cost $25,000 (60 Minutes) — programmable for different tasks daily
- Robot limitations: robots at robot competition "fell every which way"; MIT's Daniela Rus — robotic reasoning limited to programmed scope; "Have I been here before?" extremely difficult for robots; encountering unplanned situations → robot enters error state and stops
- Laundry folding example: "No machine can yet match a human's dexterity and problem-solving abilities when attacking a pile of irregular shaped clothes of different fabric types and weight"
- Amazon warehouses: Kiva robots do NOT touch merchandise — only lift shelves and bring to human packers; tactile discrimination beyond current capability
- Complementarity theme (Autor): machines substitute for labor AND complement labor — "most work processes draw upon multifaceted inputs: creativity and rote repetition, technical mastery and intuitive judgment" — improvements in one don't obviate need for the other
- ATMs created MORE bank branches; barcode scanners work alongside checkout clerks — job destruction from robots often greatly exaggerated
- 3D printing: reduces design prototyping time (days vs. months); dental crown from 2 visits to 1; but "not expected to have much effect on mass production"
- Big data / AI: mostly used for marketing — corporate IT expenditures for marketing growing at 3x rate of other IT expenditures; airlines' revenue management (JetBlue: 25 employees must constantly override computers); Macy's algorithmic personalization
- AI in professional fields: medical diagnosis, loan approvals, "robo-advisers" (Vanguard, Schwab) — but humans still working alongside, not replaced

## Pages 701–720

**Chapter 17 Conclusion: The Big Picture**
- Robo-advisers (Vanguard, Schwab): assets under management still less than $20 billion vs. $17 TRILLION for traditional human advisers — barely made a dent
- Legal AI: computerized search tools reducing demand for legal associates; "computers will move nearer to the heart of what lawyers do by advising better than lawyers can on whether to sue or settle" — but this has been true for two decades without boosting TFP
- Key paradox: quantity of electronic data has been rising exponentially for decades WITHOUT pushing TFP out of post-1970 lethargy, except temporarily 1994–2004
- Smartphone (2007) and smart tablet (2010) introductions: NO measurable response in TFP growth whatsoever
- Driverless cars: "demoted to last place" — benefits minor compared to the invention of the car itself or the 10-fold safety improvement since 1950
- Driverless car passenger benefit: instead of listening to radio or Bluetooth, passengers can read or check email — "relatively minor" consumer surplus addition
- Driverless TRUCKS more interesting: BUT drivers of Coca-Cola/bread delivery trucks don't just drive — they manually load dollies and place goods on store shelves; "almost all placement of individual product cans, bottles, and tubes on retail shelves is achieved today by humans rather than robots"
- Google car limitation: doesn't drive on roads — compares sensors to "painstakingly hand-curated maps"; any deviation (road detour, crossing guard) causes software to blank out and requires human takeover
- AI/robots "find the robot" game: besides ATMs, only the airport e-kiosk check-in (rolled out 2001–2005) is a commonly encountered robot; all other airport personnel remain; goods placed on shelves by humans; checkout lanes manned by clerks; haircuts/massages/manicures exclusively human; hotel front desk human; room service human
- Two competing visions: techno-optimists predict rapid productivity growth + mass unemployment; techno-pessimists predict "more of the same" — slow productivity growth + continued employment growth
- Numbers don't lie: unemployment fell 10.0% (Oct 2009) → 5.3% (Jun 2015); labor productivity grew only 0.5%/yr in five years ending 2Q 2015 vs. 2.3%/yr in 1994–2004
- Real problem: not mass unemployment but "gradual disappearance of good, steady, middle-level jobs" lost to robots, globalization, and outsourcing — replaced by routine manual jobs at low wages
- Chapter 17 conclusion: IR #3 "utterly changing the way Americans obtain information and communicate" but did NOT extend across full span of human life as IR #2 did; three IR #2 offshoots reached current form 40+ years ago with only minor changes since: interstate highway travel, jet air travel, ubiquitous air conditioning

**Chapter 18 Introduction: Inequality and the Four Headwinds**
- Opening epigraph: "For the first time, America's children will almost certainly not be as well educated, healthy, or wealthy as their parents." — June Carbone and Naomi Cahn, 2014
- Chapter thesis: even if labor productivity/TFP improves, four headwinds prevent most Americans from enjoying growth equal to economy-wide output per hour
- Four headwinds: (1) Inequality, (2) Education, (3) Demographics, (4) Government debt
- Real median disposable income will grow "barely positive" — far below the rate enjoyed by generations dating back to the 19th century
- Signs of social breakdown: children in single-parent households, vocabulary gap between middle-class and poverty-raised children, incarceration rates for young men

**The First Headwind: Dimensions of Rising Inequality**
- Piketty and Saez data (back to 1917, 4 years after U.S. income tax introduction in 1914) — three eras:
  - 1917–48: incomes became MORE equal — bottom 90% grew 1.43%/yr, top 10% grew only 0.58%/yr; due to Great Depression, WWII, New Deal programs (minimum wage, union legislation, GI Bill)
  - 1948–72: GOLDEN AGE — all three groups grew at roughly SAME rate; average growth 2.58%/yr — high school graduates could work unionized jobs and afford suburban house, two cars; 5x the income growth of 1972–2013
  - 1972–2013: GREAT DIVERGENCE — average real income bottom 90% actually LOWER in 2013 than 1972; peak bottom-90% real income was $37,053 (2000), barely above $35,411 (1972); by 2013 had fallen 15% to $31,652; top 10% average income DOUBLED from $161,000 (1972) to $324,000 (2007)
- Census Bureau data (1975–2013): mean real household income growth exceeded median growth by 0.47 percentage points per year — 0.61 pts during 1975–95, 0.33 pts during 1995–2012
- CBO data (adjusts for taxes and transfers): most comprehensive measure; pre-tax market income grew 1.16%/yr for average (1979–2011); after taxes and transfers grew 1.48%/yr
  - Top 1%: 3.82% pre-tax → 4.05% post-tax/transfers (market income growth)
  - 81–99 percentile: 1.39% → 1.60%
  - 20–80 percentile: 0.46% → 1.05%
  - 1–20 percentile: 0.46% → 1.23% (biggest relative improvement from transfers)
- CBO "median shortfall": median grows 0.43 percentage points SLOWER than average after adjusting for taxes and transfers — means a projection of 1.0%/yr average growth = only 0.6%/yr median growth

**Downward Pressure on Wages: Causes of the Great Divergence**
- "Great Compression" (Goldin and Margo): three supports — rise of unionization, decline of trade, decline of immigration (all dating from 1930s)
- Unionization reversal: 27% (1973) → 19% (1986) → 13% (2011) — market forces (manufacturing shrinkage, shift to services) + aggressive employer anti-union stance
- Temporary staffing agencies: manufacturing/construction firms increasingly hire temps at low wages with few benefits — lower cost + flexibility for employers
- Import share of GDP: 5.4% (1970) → 16.5% (2014) — labor embodied in imports substitutes for domestic labor

## Pages 721–740

**Causes of Wage Stagnation: Imports, Immigration, Automation, Minimum Wage**
- China imports: David Autor et al. calculated imports from China 1990–2007 accounted for about a QUARTER of the decline in manufacturing employment + lowered wages + reduced labor force participation + raised transfer payments
- Auto parts imports: doubled from $63B (2001) to $138B (2014) → automotive parts industry median wages fell from $18.35 (2003) to $15.83/hr (2013)
- Immigration: foreign-born share of labor force 5.3% (1970) → 14.7% (2005); accounted for more than half of total labor force growth 1995–2005; reduces wages by "small amount," greatest effect on domestic workers lacking high school degree
- Foreign-born vs. domestic high school dropouts: wages almost identical up to 1980; by 2004, foreign-born earned 15–20% less — driving down wages of immigrants, not primarily domestic workers
- Automation / "skill-biased technical change": manufacturing share of employment fell from 30% (1953) to <10% currently; routine jobs destroyed (typist, bookkeeper, clerk, receptionist)
- Polarization hypothesis: job growth at top ("non-routine abstract") and bottom ("manual"), hollowing out of middle ("routine"); middle-skilled workers forced to compete for low-skilled jobs → drives down manual wages
- Minimum wage (constant 2011 dollars): $8.38 (1979) → $5.87 (1989) → low of $4.68 (2006) → $7.25 (2009)
- CEO pay vs. worker pay: 20x average worker pay (1973) → 257x average worker pay (2013); average CEO pay of publicly traded companies = $10.5 million
- Caterpillar Corporation example: broke strikes to enforce two-tier wage system; new hires paid HALF of existing workers; CEO compensation +80% in 2011–13; CEO's mantra: "we can never make enough money, we can never make enough profit"
- Target CEO example: replaced after credit card data breach in May 2014; received $47 million retirement package — roughly 1,000x the average worker's 401(k) balance at Target
- "Detroit Consensus" (Levy and Temin): 1940s policy with 90% marginal tax rates sent signal that high incomes were unacceptable; Reagan "Washington Consensus" tax cuts began to erode this
- Manufacturing recovery 2009–13: regained only 600,000 of 6 million jobs lost since 2001 — and most at substantially lower wages

**Inequality at the Top**
- Three groups at the top: (1) Superstars (sports, entertainment), (2) High-skilled professionals (lawyers, investment bankers), (3) CEOs and corporate officers
- Superstar economics (Sherwin Rosen): audiences want the best, not second-best; top performer exerts same effort whether 10 or 10,000 witness; innovations (phonograph → cable TV → streaming → YouTube) multiplied audience size → multiplied superstar income
- CEO pay: NOT set purely by market — Lucian Bebchuk and Yaniv Grinstein show "managerial power hypothesis" drives CEO pay above market; top-five compensation as % of corporate profits rose from 5.0% (1993–95) to 12.8% (2000–2002)
- Stock options: preferred because less visible, less likely to incite stockholder anger; stock market returns 1983 (S&P at 120) to 2000 (S&P at 1477) = 14.3% real annual return including dividends
- Bottom 80% and wealth: Federal Reserve study — 5+ million households SOLD OUT of stock market when it was low in 2009–10; only top 10% increased stock holdings since then
- Pew Research wealth by group 1983–2013: upper 21% — wealth doubled from $318,100 to $639,400; middle 46% — wealth stagnated from $94,300 to $96,500; bottom 33% — wealth FELL from $11,400 to $9,300

**Education as a Source of Inequality (Second Headwind)**
- College-educated vs. high school graduate wage gap (2012): $35,000/yr for men, $23,000/yr for women; dual college-graduate household earns $58,000/yr more than dual high-school-graduate household
- Present discounted value of college degree by 2008: $590,000 for men, $370,000 for women
- College wage premium: declined slightly in 1970s (surge in college graduates); rose steadily from 1982–2001 (slower relative supply growth); flatlined after 2005
- Post-2000 reversal: college graduates increasingly forced into jobs not requiring college; decline in non-routine abstract jobs after dot-com bust
- College completion rate: U.S. ranked 2nd in world (2000) → now ranked 12th; 25–34 age group with BA degree: inched up from 25% to only 32% in 15 years
- University cost rise: since 1972, university costs have risen at MORE THAN TRIPLE the overall rate of inflation; state funding for higher education declined by a THIRD (2001–2012, inflation-adjusted)
- Colorado example: state provided 37% of University of Colorado budget (1985) → only 9% (2013)
- Total student debt: Americans owe $1.2 trillion; underemployment rate for 22-year-old college graduates = 56% (unable to find jobs requiring college degree); 40% for 27-year-olds
- High school graduation: increased from <10% (1900) to 80% (1970) → FELL to 74% (2000); U.S. ranked 11th in developed nations in high school graduation; only developed country where 25–34 graduation rate is NO HIGHER than 55–64 graduation rate
- PISA 2013: U.S. ranked 17th in reading, 20th in science, 27th in math; ACT found only 25% of high school students prepared for college
- Community college: enrolls 39% of undergraduates; only 13% graduate in 2 years; only 28% after 4 years
- Preschool: 70% average enrollment of 3-year-olds in rich nations vs. 38% in U.S.
- Property tax financing creates vicious circle: wealthy suburbs = lavish schools + educated parents → poor districts = budget cuts, school closings
- Self-perpetuating educational elite: college completion top-quartile income households rose from 40% (1970) to 77% (2013); bottom-quartile rose from only 6% to 9%

**Third Headwind: Demographics**
- Key identity: output per person (Y/N) = labor productivity (Y/H) × hours per person (H/N)
- H/N can be decomposed into: hours per employee × employment rate × labor force participation rate
- Baby boom (1946–1964) retirement: started 2008, extends to 2034 — reduces hours per person; scholars estimate –0.4%/yr drag on output per person relative to labor productivity
- Labor force participation rate: 66.0% (2007) → 62.6% (June 2015) = 3.4 percentage point decline = loss of 8.5 million jobs, most permanent
- Scranton, PA: 41.3% of those older than 18 withdrawn from workforce; Syracuse, NY: 42.4% — post-deindustrialization devastation
- British consul-general in Chicago (autumn 2013): "What surprised me most was the deterioration and decay of the former one-factory small and middle-sized manufacturing towns"

**Fourth Headwind: Government Debt**
- CBO baseline forecast: debt-to-GDP ratio stabilizes 2014–2020, then rises to 100% by 2038
- Gordon's projection: more pessimistic than CBO — 87% by 2024 (CBO: 78%); ~125% by 2038 (CBO: 100%)
- Medicare trust fund reaches zero: 2030; Social Security trust fund zero: 2034
- Detroit bankruptcy as warning for Illinois, Chicago, other states with massive unfunded pension liabilities
- Gordon's estimate: fiscal reckoning will reduce growth of disposable income by 0.1%/yr relative to pre-tax income

**Social Breakdown at the Bottom**
- Marriage collapse among non-college Americans: only 65 employed men for every 100 women of a given age; for young African Americans, only 51 employed men per 100 women (high incarceration)
- White high school graduates — out-of-wedlock births: 4% (1982) → 34% (2008); dropouts: 21% → 42%
- Black high school graduates — out-of-wedlock births: 48% → 74%; dropouts: 76% → 96%
- Charles Murray's "Fishtown" data (bottom third of white population, 1960–2010): married couples with spouse working 40+ hrs/wk: 84% → 58%; percent married 85% → 48%; never married 8% → 25%; divorced 5% → 33%; children living with both biological parents (mothers aged 40): 95% → 34%
- White male high school dropouts who have been in prison: 3.8% (1979) → 28.0% (2009)
- Black male high school dropouts: 14.7% (1979) → 68.0% (2009) — TWO-THIRDS of all black male high school dropouts spend at least one spell in prison by age 40

## Pages 741–760

**Social Decline Continued**
- 1/3 of all adult Americans have some kind of criminal record (FBI data) — major barrier to employment
- Electronic records make it easier for employers to find past criminal history; state laws prohibit convicted felons from occupational roles ranging from child care to barbers and hairdressers
- Criminal record → less employment → less marriage attractiveness → reinforces social decline cycle

**Other Headwinds: Globalization and Environment**
- Globalization: roughly half of the 7 million manufacturing job loss 2000–2011 occurred BEFORE the 2008 financial crisis; peak Chinese manufacturing impact 2000–2007; housing bubble temporarily absorbed displaced workers into construction
- Foreign automotive investment exclusively in right-to-work southern states: $15–$20/hr vs. $30–$40/hr in pre-2007 union states; workers in south "welcomed as manna from heaven"; classic factor price equalization
- Global warming (William Nordhaus): a 3°C warming over 70 years would reduce global GDP by only ~2.5% — translates to 0.036 percentage points per year drag, trivial compared to demography headwind of –0.4%
- Fracking: oil price still set by world markets; gas fracking more beneficial because gas can't easily be transported between continents → cheaper domestic gas unique to North America

**Chapter 18 Conclusion: Quantifying the Forecast**
- Labor productivity growth record: 2.71%/yr (1948–70) → 1.54%/yr (1970–94) → 2.26%/yr (1994–2004) → 1.00%/yr (2004–15)
- Gordon's forecast: 1994–2004 was "one-time event" — leaving it aside, 1970–94 and 2004–15 weighted average = 1.38%/yr; subtract 0.3 pts for education headwind → 1.08% adjusted; round up to 1.20%/yr for optimism
- Reality check: actual productivity growth in 5 years ending Q2 2015 = only 0.50%/yr (Gordon's 1.20% forecast is therefore already optimistic)
- Hours per person: baby-boom retirement → –0.4%/yr reduction in H/N through 2015–34
- Output per person = productivity (1.20%) + H/N change (–0.40%) = 0.80%/yr — vs. 2.41%/yr (1920–70) and 1.77%/yr (1970–2014)
- Inequality headwind: median income growing 0.43%/yr slower than average → median real income growth = 0.80% – 0.40% = 0.40%/yr
- Fiscal headwind: future tax increases/transfer payment cuts will reduce disposable income growth by additional 0.1%/yr
- BOTTOM LINE: real median disposable income projected to grow only 0.3%/yr for 2015–2040 — compared to 2.1%/yr for the near-century 1920–2014
- "An exercise in subtraction" — innovation slowdown + four headwinds convert historically remarkable growth to "barely positive"

**Postscript: America's Growth Achievement and the Path Ahead**
- Book's message is NOT about failure — it's that rapid growth was remarkable and inevitable to slow because many transformations "could only happen once" (running water, washing machine, infant mortality conquest)
- 1870–1970 was "unique": food, clothing, housing, transportation, entertainment, communication, health, working conditions all transformed
- Post-1970 innovation excelled in entertainment, ICT — but didn't transform full span of life
- U.S. strengths: top 8 of 10 most valuable companies in world are American; venture capital industry; government-funded science and DARPA Internet roots; shale oil/gas; top 30 universities dominated by U.S. institutions; higher fertility + immigration vs. aging Europe/Japan
- Post-2008 recovery: unemployment 10% (late 2009) → ~5% (2015) vs. >11% in Eurozone; creating 2.5 million jobs/year

**Postscript: Policy Recommendations**
- Tax progressivity: top 1% income share nearly TRIPLED from 8% (1974) to 22% (2014); top 0.01% quintupled from 1% to 5%; CEO-to-worker pay ratio: 22x (1973) → 352x (2007) → CEO pay captured 12.8% of corporate profits 2000–02 (vs. 5% in 1993–95); proposed "super-bracket" tax rates for those earning >$1M and >$10M; make capital gains/dividends taxed like regular income (was in effect 1993–97)
- Minimum wage: currently $7.25 = 12% LESS than the 1960s average in 2014 prices; real compensation per hour rose 115% over 50 years — minimum wage didn't keep up; Gordon supports raising it
- Earned Income Tax Credit (EITC): reduces incidence of low birth weight, raises math/reading scores, boosts college enrollment for beneficiaries' children; expand and make more generous; complements (not substitute for) minimum wage
- Incarceration: U.S. rate 8–10x higher than largest European countries; costs taxpayers $74 billion/year; 60% released from prison unemployed one year after release; "widespread movement toward pardoning" needed; cash bail reform; shorter sentences; drug treatment/mental health for released prisoners
- Drug legalization: cost of prohibition = $88 billion/year (Jeffrey Miron and Katherine Waldock, 2010); half saved through enforcement/court/prison costs; half = foregone tax revenue (if taxed like tobacco)
- Preschool: universal in Japan and UK for 4-year-olds; U.S. only 69% of 4-year-olds enrolled (ranked 26th OECD); only 50% of 3-year-olds vs. 90%+ in France and Italy; James Heckman: experimental preschool programs yield 7–10%/yr return per dollar invested (higher than elementary/secondary spending); by age 5 brain already "built the cognitive and character skills critical for future success" — too late to intervene
- Secondary/higher education: property tax financing creates lavish rich suburbs vs. run-down inner city schools; shift financing from local to statewide revenue; Australia model for student debt — free college, repay through income tax based on % of income; no payment if unemployed
- Regressive regulation: copyright laws too broad (criminalize noncommercial copying); patent laws overreaching (software and business methods); occupational licensing rose from 10% (1970) to 30% (2008) of jobs — restricts entry, limits mobility; restrictive zoning inflates housing prices in productive metro areas, forces less-productive migration (Edward Glaeser's "regulatory tax")

## Pages 761–780

**Postscript: Policy (Continued) and Closing**
- Tax reform: Martin Feldstein's plan to limit "tax expenditures" (all deductions disproportionately benefit high earners vs. tax credits) would raise federal revenues by $144 billion/year without ending charitable deductions
- Carbon tax: CBO estimates $20/ton CO2 tax would raise $115 billion/year; can be used to avoid raising payroll taxes or cutting retirement benefits
- Policy table (10 categories): all 10 address inequality; 7 of 10 also boost productivity growth: EITC, incarceration/drug reform, preschool, public school finance, income-contingent loans, regressive regulations, immigration
- Immigration reform: Canada's point-based system as model; U.S. annual legal immigration = 0.3% of population vs. Canada's 0.8%; end policy of denying residency to foreign-born graduates of U.S. universities ("self-imposed brain drain")
- Gordon's final assessment: even if ALL proposed policies were implemented, boost to median disposable income would be "no more than a few tenths of a percent above the rate without policy changes" — but would create "more equal, better-educated society"
- Book's authorship origin: Otto Bettmann's The Bad Old Days: They Were Really Terrible (found at bed & breakfast in Michigan in 1980s) → Gordon's 2000 article "Does the New Economy Measure Up to the Great Inventions of the Past?" → book suggestion from David Warsh and Seth Ditchk (Princeton UP editor) at AEA 2007
- Book title credit: Seth Ditchik of Princeton University Press
- Robert Solow: supervised Gordon's MIT PhD on the same 1920–50 productivity puzzle; read five chapters in summer of 2014 (during Solow's 90th birthday)
- The book's final dedication: to Gordon's wife Julie of 52 years; reference to Gershwin and the Great American Songbook as "another achievement of America's great leap forward from the 1920s to the 1950s"

**Data Appendix: Technical Notes on Capital Measurement**
- Official BEA capital stock data shows private capital STOPPED GROWING 1929–1944 — "raises red flags" — this is a data artifact, not reality
- BEA uses perpetual inventory method with FIXED depreciation schedules that don't respond to economic conditions; this systematically overstates depreciation during low-investment periods
- Buildings example: Empire State Building (1931) not surpassed as NYC's tallest until World Trade Center (1974); Chicago Board of Trade (1930) not surpassed until Prudential Tower (1957) — no empty lots appeared in 1930s Manhattan, buildings stayed in use
- Machine tools: % more than 10 years old jumped from 46% (1930) to 71% (1940) — proving old equipment was retained, not scrapped on BEA's fixed schedule
- Structures investment/capital ratio: fell from 4.8% average (1925–29) to 1.1% in 1933; didn't exceed 4.0% until 1946 — average 1931–45 was only 39% of 1925–29 average
- Gordon's "variable retirement" adjustment: multiplies BEA depreciation by I/K ratio relative to its historical mean; 1933 example: actual I/K was 6.9% vs. mean of 15.4% → adjustment factor 0.45 → depreciation drops from $12.7B to $5.7B (1950 dollars)
- User cost weights for equipment: Jorgenson-Griliches (1967) framework; equipment depreciates faster than structures (laptop replaced every 3–5 years; tractor 12–15 years; buildings 90+ years); equipment/structures multiplier rises gradually from 3.0 (1925) to 5.9 (2013)
- Adding government capital: WWII government-financed factories were enormous — federal government purchased productive equipment 1941–45 equal to ~50% of 1941 private equipment stock; official BEA data excludes this because it was government-owned (though operated privately)
- These capital adjustments reduce (but don't eliminate) the measured Great Leap in TFP — confirming genuine productivity acceleration even after correcting for capital measurement errors

## Pages 781–800

**Data Appendix: Government Capital (Continued)**
- Government capital rose relative to private structures throughout 1930s (New Deal highway construction); peaked at end of WWII (1944)
- Government structures as % of private non-residential structures: 35.4% (1928) → 58.0% (1941) → 68.6% (1944) — nearly doubled over 16 years
- Government capital remained high post-WWII: 66.1% (1950) → 74.9% (1957) → 93.4% (1972) — driven by interstate highway construction
- Key fact: Willow Run B-24 bomber plant was paid for by the U.S. federal government, not Ford Motor Company — counted as government capital, not private capital
- Capital revision summary (Table A-2): revised vs. official capital, 1928–1972:
  - 1941: official capital up 4.2% from 1928 vs. revised capital up 25.1% — gap of 20.9%
  - 1944: official up 2.6% vs. revised up 30.9% — gap of 28.3%; of that: 15.7% from variable depreciation, 4.6% from reweighting equipment, 8.0% from government capital
  - These revisions reduce (but don't eliminate) the measured TFP jump between 1920s and 1950s

