Chapter 6
FROM TELEGRAPH TO TALKIES:
INFORMATION, COMMUNICATION, AND
ENTERTAINMENT
When Charlie Chaplin was eight, he performed in three large music
halls an evening. Ten years later, in 1915, each night he could be
seen in thousands of halls across the world. The remarkable
transformation of spectating into a non-rival setting where Chaplin
could be watched in many places simultaneously was made possible
by motion pictures. They industrialized entertainment by automating
it, standardizing it, and making it tradable.
—Bakker (2012), p. 1036
